{"Status": "Complete", "Paper Overview": {"type_of_reference": "JOUR", "Title": "Size-Luminosity Relations and UV Luminosity Functions at z = 6-9 Simultaneously Derived from the Complete Hubble Frontier Fields Data", "authors": ["Kawamata, Ryota", "Ishigaki, Masafumi", "Shimasaku, Kazuhiro", "Oguri, Masamune", "Ouchi, Masami", "Tanigawa, Shingo"], "author_address": ["AA(Department of Astronomy, Graduate School of Science, The University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan), AB(Department of Physics, Graduate School of Science, The University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan ; Institute for Cosmic Ray Research, The University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8582, Japan), AC(Department of Astronomy, Graduate School of Science, The University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan; Research Center for the Early Universe, The University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan ; Kavli Institute for the Physics and Mathematics of the Universe (Kavli IPMU, WPI), The University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8583, Japan), AE(Institute for Cosmic Ray Research, The University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8582, Japan ; Kavli Institute for the Physics and Mathematics of the Universe (Kavli IPMU, WPI), The University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8583, Japan), AF(Department of Astronomy, Graduate School of Science, The University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan; Institute of Astronomy, University of Cambridge, Madingley Road, Cambridge, CB3 0HA, UK)"], "journal_name": "The Astrophysical Journal", "volume": "855", "publication_year": "2018/03/1", "start_page": "4", "keywords": ["galaxies: evolution", "galaxies: high-redshift", "galaxies: structure", "gravitational lensing: strong", "Astrophysics - Astrophysics of Galaxies"], "url": "https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...855....4K", "abstract": "We construct z \u223c 6-7, 8, and 9 faint Lyman break galaxy samples (334, 61, and 37 galaxies, respectively) with accurate size measurements with the software glafic from the complete Hubble Frontier Fields (HFF) cluster and parallel fields data. These are the largest samples hitherto and reach down to the faint ends of recently obtained deep luminosity functions. At faint magnitudes, however, these samples are highly incomplete for galaxies with large sizes, implying that derivation of the luminosity function sensitively depends on the intrinsic size-luminosity relation. We thus conduct simultaneous maximum-likelihood estimation of luminosity function and size-luminosity relation parameters from the observed distribution of galaxies on the size-luminosity plane with the help of a completeness map as a function of size and luminosity. At z \u223c 6-7, we find that the intrinsic size-luminosity relation expressed as r <SUB>e</SUB> \u221d L <SUP> \u03b2 </SUP> has a notably steeper slope of \u03b2 ={0.46}<SUB>-0.09</SUB><SUP>+0.08</SUP> than those at lower redshifts, which in turn implies that the luminosity function has a relatively shallow faint-end slope of \u03b1 =-{1.86}<SUB>-0.18</SUB><SUP>+0.17</SUP>. This steep \u03b2 can be reproduced by a simple analytical model in which smaller galaxies have lower specific angular momenta. The \u03b2 and \u03b1 values for the z \u223c 8 and 9 samples are consistent with those for z \u223c 6-7 but with larger errors. For all three samples, there is a large, positive covariance between \u03b2 and \u03b1, implying that the simultaneous determination of these two parameters is important. We also provide new strong lens mass models of Abell S1063 and Abell 370, as well as updated mass models of Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1-2403.", "doi": "10.3847/1538-4357/aaa6cf", "custom1": "eprint: arXiv:1710.07301", "issn": "0004-637X", "number": "1"}, "ADS link": "https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...855....4K", "Publisher link via ADS gateway": "https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/link_gateway/2018ApJ...855....4K/PUB_HTML", "Action": "Scanned and processed all tables", "Paper text": "<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"ISO-8859-1\" ?>\n<!DOCTYPE article PUBLIC \"-//NLM//DTD Journal Publishing DTD v3.0 20080202//EN\" \"http://ej.iop.org/dtd/nlm-3.0/journalpublishing3.dtd\">\n<article xmlns:mml=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" article-type=\"research-article\">\n<front>\n<journal-meta>\n<journal-id journal-id-type=\"publisher-id\">apj</journal-id>\n<journal-title-group>\n<journal-title>The Astrophysical Journal</journal-title>\n<abbrev-journal-title abbrev-type=\"AAS\">APJ</abbrev-journal-title>\n<abbrev-journal-title abbrev-type=\"publisher\">Astrophys. content-type=\"short-author-list\">\n<p>Kawamata et al.</p>\n</author-comment>\n</contrib-group>\n<pub-date pub-type=\"ppub\">\n<day>1</day>\n<month>3</month>\n<year>2018</year>\n</pub-date>\n<pub-date pub-type=\"epub\">\n<day>27</day>\n<month>02</month>\n<year>2018</year>\n</pub-date>\n<volume>855</volume>\n<issue>1</issue>\n<elocation-id content-type=\"artnum\">4</elocation-id>\n<history>\n<date date-type=\"received\">\n<day>17</day>\n<month>10</month>\n<year>2017</year>\n</date>\n<date date-type=\"rev-recd\">\n<day>8</day>\n<month>12</month>\n<year>2017</year>\n</date>\n<date date-type=\"accepted\">\n<day>4</day>\n<month>1</month>\n<year>2018</year>\n</date>\n</history>\n<permissions>\n<copyright-statement>&copy; 2018. The American Astronomical Society. All rights reserved.</copyright-statement>\n<copyright-year>2018</copyright-year>\n</permissions>\n<self-uri xlink:href=\"http://stacks.iop.org/apj/855/4\"/>\n<abstract>\n<title>Abstract</title>\n<p>We construct <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9 faint Lyman break galaxy samples (334, 61, and 37 galaxies, respectively) with accurate size measurements with the software <monospace>glafic</monospace> from the complete <italic>Hubble</italic> Frontier Fields (HFF) cluster and parallel fields data. These are the largest samples hitherto and reach down to the faint ends of recently obtained deep luminosity functions. At faint magnitudes, however, these samples are highly incomplete for galaxies with large sizes, implying that derivation of the luminosity function sensitively depends on the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation. We thus conduct simultaneous maximum-likelihood estimation of luminosity function and size&ndash;luminosity relation parameters from the observed distribution of galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane with the help of a completeness map as a function of size and luminosity. At <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, we find that the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation expressed as <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&prop;&nbsp;<italic>L</italic><sup><italic>&beta;</italic></sup> has a notably steeper slope of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta ={0.46}_{-0.09}^{+0.08}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.46</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.09</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.08</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn1.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> than those at lower redshifts, which in turn implies that the luminosity function has a relatively shallow faint-end slope of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\alpha =-{1.86}_{-0.18}^{+0.17}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.86</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.18</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.17</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn2.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. This steep <italic>&beta;</italic> can be reproduced by a simple analytical model in which smaller galaxies have lower specific angular momenta. The <italic>&beta;</italic> and <italic>&agr;</italic> values for the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9 samples are consistent with those for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 but with larger errors. For all three samples, there is a large, positive covariance between <italic>&beta;</italic> and <italic>&agr;</italic>, implying that the simultaneous determination of these two parameters is important. We also provide new strong lens mass models of Abell S1063 and Abell 370, as well as updated mass models of Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403.</p>\n</abstract>\n<kwd-group kwd-group-type=\"AAS\">\n<kwd>galaxies: evolution</kwd>\n<kwd>galaxies: high-redshift</kwd>\n<kwd>galaxies: structure</kwd>\n<kwd>gravitational lensing: strong</kwd>\n</kwd-group>\n<counts>\n<page-count count=\"47\"/>\n</counts>\n<custom-meta-group>\n<custom-meta>\n<meta-name>ccc</meta-name>\n<meta-value>0004-637X/18/4&plus;47&dollar;33.00</meta-value>\n</custom-meta>\n<custom-meta>\n<meta-name>crossmark</meta-name>\n<meta-value>yes</meta-value>\n</custom-meta>\n</custom-meta-group>\n</article-meta>\n</front>\n<body>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs1\">\n<label>1.</label>\n<title>Introduction</title>\n<p>Disk sizes of galaxies at very high redshifts are important in two aspects. One is that they provide information on the formation and early evolution of galaxies. The other is that they have a significant effect on the determination of UV luminosity functions because the correction for detection incompleteness sensitively depends on size.</p>\n<p>Concerning the first aspect, the size of galaxies is largely determined by their angular momentum (e.g., Fall &amp; Efstathiou <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib37\">1980</xref>; Mo et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib77\">1998</xref>), as is the case for disk galaxies, and angular momentum is one of the fundamental parameters of galaxies as argued by Fall (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib36\">1983</xref>). Romanowsky &amp; Fall (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib99\">2012</xref>) and Fall &amp; Romanowsky (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib38\">2013</xref>) discussed galaxy formation and evolution using the specific angular momentum&ndash;mass diagram. Indeed, numerous simulations and analytical models of galaxy formation suggest that the size of galaxies changes with a redistribution of the angular momentum in them due to stellar feedback such as galactic winds (e.g., Brooks et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib18\">2011</xref>; Wyithe &amp; Loeb <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib110\">2011</xref>; Brook et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib17\">2012</xref>; Danovich et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib29\">2015</xref>; Genel et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib42\">2015</xref>). Recently, high-resolution cosmological simulations have succeeded in increasing sizes at a fixed luminosity or stellar mass of simulated galaxies to reproduce observed sizes by incorporating stellar feedback such as galactic winds of high mass-loading factors (e.g., Brooks et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib18\">2011</xref>; Genel et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib42\">2015</xref>). The luminosity dependence of the size is also affected by stellar feedback as explained by simple analytical models. For example, Wyithe &amp; Loeb (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib110\">2011</xref>) showed that the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation varies depending on the dominating feedback, such as energy-driven and momentum-driven feedback. Larger sizes indicate more efficient feedback, which suggests that the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation contains information on the dominant feedback process.</p>\n<p>The second aspect concerning UV luminosity functions is also important because luminosity functions are determined by correcting for detection completeness, which depends on the intrinsic size distribution. For a given magnitude, galaxies with larger sizes are less likely to be detected because of their lower surface brightness. Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib45\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2011</xref>), based on the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 analysis, pointed out that the assumed size distribution critically alters the UV luminosity function, especially the faint-end slope.</p>\n<p>One of the main goals of recent observational projects targeting <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6 galaxies (e.g., Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>; Grogin et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib47\">2011</xref>; Koekemoer et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib65a\">2011</xref>; Ellis et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib35\">2013</xref>; Illingworth et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib55a\">2013</xref>; Ono et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib87\">2018</xref>) is to obtain the faint-end slope of luminosity functions, a key quantity for testing galaxy formation models. In addition, since <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;10 is the epoch of reionization and faint galaxies are thought to be major sources of ionizing photons, the abundance of faint galaxies, i.e., the faint-end slope, is important for understanding the reionization of the universe.</p>\n<p>Recently, in order to derive luminosity functions at fainter magnitudes, deep observations combined with the power of the gravitational lensing by galaxy clusters have been conducted, such as the CLASH program (see Postman et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib91\">2012</xref> for more details) and the <italic>Hubble</italic> Frontier Fields program (HFF; Lotz et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib71\">2017</xref>). Utilizing early-stage data from the HFF, the faint limits of luminosity functions reach as faint as UV magnitudes (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>) of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;15.5, &minus;17, and &minus;17.5 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively (Atek et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib3\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>, <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib4\">2015b</xref>; Ishigaki et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib55\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>; McLeod et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib74\">2015</xref>). More recently, very faint galaxies of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;13 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 have been detected using one-third of the full HFF data (Castellano et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib24\">2016</xref>; Livermore et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib70\">2017</xref>), half of them (Laporte et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>), two-thirds of them (Kawamata et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">2016</xref>, hereafter <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">K16</xref>; Yue et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib111\">2017</xref>), and all of them (Ishigaki et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>). However, the luminosity functions obtained in the previous studies, including those from the HFF, are still highly uncertain, especially at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;&minus;18 and <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6, because the size&ndash;luminosity relations are not determined well in that magnitude range (see our Figure 12 and Figure 2 of Bouwens et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) owing to an insufficient number of galaxies with size measurements.</p>\n<p>There have been a number of studies that measure sizes of bright (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;18) galaxies (e.g., Bouwens et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib10\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2004</xref>; Ferguson et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib39\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2004</xref>; Curtis-Lake et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib28\">2016</xref>; Laporte et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>; Bowler et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib15\">2017</xref>). At <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4 and 5, Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) carefully measured the size distributions of Lyman break galaxies (LBGs) with &minus;22.5&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;17.5 and found size&ndash;luminosity relations of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.22-0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.22</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn3.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, where <italic>L</italic> and <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub> are the luminosity and effective half-light radius, respectively. Oesch et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>) were among the first to measure the sizes of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 and 8 galaxies with samples of 16 and five galaxies from HUDF09 (Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib81\">2010b</xref>), reporting that the decreasing trend of sizes with increasing redshifts continues to these redshifts. This trend was confirmed by Ono et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib86\">2013</xref>) by careful measurements using the deeper imaging data from HUDF12 (Ellis et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib35\">2013</xref>; Koekemoer et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib65\">2013</xref>). With a larger sample, Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib44\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2012</xref>) measured the sizes of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 LBGs of moderate magnitude (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;18.5). They found that the size&ndash;luminosity relation is in the form of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.5}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.5</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn4.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at this redshift, although their size measurements may suffer from systematic biases due to their measuring method. More recently, Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) measured sizes for large <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&minus;10 LBG samples with moderate magnitudes of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;18. However, since none of the above studies has reliably determined the size&ndash;luminosity relation for <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;18 galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6, a size&ndash;luminosity relation of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn5.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> has been commonly adopted, given the results of Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) obtained for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;5. This relation is extrapolated and also applied to fainter magnitudes down to <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;13, beyond the magnitude range over which it is determined.</p>\n<p>At faint magnitudes of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;&minus;18, Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>; hereafter <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>) used the first cluster and parallel fields data from the HFF to find that the sizes of observed faint galaxies (&minus;18.7&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;16.6) are considerably smaller than the sizes inferred from the extrapolated size&ndash;luminosity relation of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn6.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. This result was subsequently confirmed by Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>), Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>), and Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib14\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017c</xref>), who measured the sizes of faint galaxies using four, three, and four HFF cluster fields data, respectively. In addition, Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) indirectly indicated the absence of faint galaxies with large sizes using the dependence of the galaxy surface density on the lensing shear. They concluded that the intrinsic sizes of the faintest galaxies are small, and the intrinsic size distribution assumed in the calculation of the luminosity function should be close to the observed one. This makes the faint-end slope of the luminosity function shallower. However, since none of Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>), Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib14\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017c</xref>), and Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>) considered an incompleteness correction due to galaxies with large sizes, the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation may be biased toward a steeper value. In addition, the indirect inference in Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) is subject to large uncertainties, which may result in weak constraints on the size distribution compared to inferences using direct size measurements.</p>\n<p>In this paper, we provide direct size measurements of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9 LBGs at &minus;21.6&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;12.3 using all six HFF cluster and parallel fields data. We show that the incompleteness effect is significant at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9 for the first time. We derive incompleteness-corrected intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relations simultaneously with luminosity functions, which enables us to explore the correlation between these two functions. We note that we do not discuss the UV luminosity density and hence the contribution of galaxies to cosmic reionization, because the normalization parameter of UV luminosity functions is not determined in this paper.</p>\n<p>The structure of this paper is as follows. In Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs2\">2</xref>, we describe the data and samples, which are identical to those constructed in Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>) but with slight changes. In Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs3\">3</xref>, we measure the sizes of the galaxies. Our method to correct for systematic biases, which is updated from that in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> in order to deal with the increased number of galaxies, is also described. In Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs4\">4</xref>, for each of the three redshift ranges, we simultaneously estimate the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation and the UV luminosity function from the observed distribution of galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane, taking account of the incompleteness effect. The correlations between the size&ndash;luminosity and luminosity function parameters are also obtained. We discuss our findings in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5\">5</xref> and give a summary in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs6\">6</xref>.</p>\n<p>Throughout this paper, we adopt a cosmology with &OHgr;<sub><italic>M</italic></sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.3, &OHgr;<sub>&Lambda;</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.7, and <italic>H</italic><sub>0</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;70 km s<sup>&minus;1</sup> Mpc<sup>&minus;1</sup>. Magnitudes are given in the AB system (Oke &amp; Gunn <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib85\">1983</xref>). Galaxy sizes are measured in the physical scale.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs2\">\n<label>2.</label>\n<title>Data and Sample Selection</title>\n<p>Here we describe the data, sample selection, and obtained samples. The data and the criteria for the sample selection are the same as those in Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>), but we remove two galaxies from their samples. Only a brief description is given in this section, and readers are referred to the above paper for further details.</p>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs2-1\">\n<label>2.1.</label>\n<title>HFF Mosaic Data</title>\n<p>We use the reduced image mosaics obtained in the HFF program, which are made publicly available through the STScI website.<xref ref-type=\"fn\" rid=\"apjaaa6cffn1\"><sup>7</sup></xref>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cffn1\">\n<label><sup>7</sup></label>\n<p>\n<ext-link ext-link-type=\"uri\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"http://www.stsci.edu/hst/campaigns/frontier-fields/\">http://www.stsci.edu/hst/campaigns/frontier-fields/</ext-link>\n</p>\n</fn> This program targets six cluster fields&mdash;Abell 2744, MACS J0416.1&minus;2403, MACS J0717.5&plus;3745, MACS J1149.6&plus;2223, Abell S1063, and Abell 370&mdash;and their accompanying six parallel fields. Those fields have been observed deeply with the <italic>Hubble Space Telescope</italic> using three bands of the Advanced Camera for Surveys (ACS) and four bands of the IR channel of the Wide Field Camera 3 (WFC3/IR). We utilize the v1.0 standard calibrated (i.e., without &ldquo;self-calibration&rdquo;) mosaics for the three ACS bands F435W (<italic>B</italic><sub>435</sub>), F606W (<italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub>), and F814W (<italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub>). For the four WFC3/IR bands F105W (<italic>Y</italic><sub>105</sub>), F125W (<italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>), F140W (<italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>), and F160W (<italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub>), we use the v1.0 standard calibrated mosaics for the Abell 2744 parallel and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403 cluster fields and v1.0 mosaics corrected for &ldquo;time-variable sky emission&rdquo; for the other 10 fields. The 5<italic>&sgr;</italic> limiting magnitudes of the mosaics are &sim;29 mag on a 0&farcs;35 diameter aperture. All the images have a pixel scale of 0&farcs;03.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs2-2\">\n<label>2.2.</label>\n<title>Sample Selection</title>\n<p>We make two catalogs with different detection images, which are referred to as the<italic> JJHH</italic> and <italic>JHH</italic> catalogs. The detection image for the former is a <italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>, <italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>, and <italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub> combined image, and for the latter it is a <italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub> and <italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub> combined image; these are created using <monospace>SWarp</monospace> v2.38.0 (Bertin et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib9\">2002</xref>) together with their weight maps. To make the catalogs, we run <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> v2.8.6 (Bertin &amp; Arnouts <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib8\">1996</xref>) on the seven bands&rsquo; images using the detection images. The photometric redshifts of galaxies in these catalogs are estimated using <monospace>BPZ</monospace> v1.99.3 (Ben&iacute;tez <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib7\">2000</xref>). From the catalogs, we select <italic>i</italic>-, <italic>Y</italic>-, and <italic>YJ</italic>-dropout galaxies using the Lyman break technique. For <italic>i</italic>- and <italic>Y</italic>-dropout selections, we use the <italic>JJHH</italic> catalog, and for <italic>YJ</italic>-dropout selection, we use the <italic>JHH</italic> catalog. For <italic>i</italic> dropouts or <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 galaxies, we use the criteria of<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn1\">\n<label>1</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn8.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>\n<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn9\">\n<label>9</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{J}_{125}-{H}_{160}\\lt 1.15,\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>J</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>125</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>H</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>160</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.15</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn9.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>\n<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn10\">\n<label>10</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}J{H}_{140}-{H}_{160}\\lt 0.6.\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>J</mml:mi>\n<mml:mspace width=\"-0.16em\"/>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>H</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>140</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>H</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>160</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.6</mml:mn>\n<mml:mi>.</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn10.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>\n</p>\n<p>For <italic>i</italic> dropouts, we use additional signal-to-noise ratio constraints that require objects not to be detected at &gt;2<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels in both the <italic>B</italic><sub>435</sub>- and <italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub>-band images or in a <italic>B</italic><sub>435</sub> &plus; <italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub> stacked image. Detections at &gt;5<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels are also required in both the <italic>Y</italic><sub>105</sub> and <italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>-band images. For a conservative selection, <italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub> magnitudes are replaced by the <italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub> 2<italic>&sgr;</italic> limiting magnitude if the signal is below that level. For <italic>Y</italic> dropouts, objects are required to be detected at &gt;2<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels in none of the <italic>B</italic><sub>435</sub>-, <italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub>-, and <italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub>-band images. In addition, detections at &gt;5<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels are required in all of the <italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>-, <italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>-, and <italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub>-band images. For <italic>YJ</italic> dropouts, objects are required to be detected at &gt;2<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels in none of the <italic>B</italic><sub>435</sub>-, <italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub>-, and <italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub>-band images. In addition, detections at &gt;3<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels are required in all of the <italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>- and <italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub>-band images and at &gt;3.5<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels in at least one of these band images. Magnitudes of <italic>Y</italic><sub>105</sub> and <italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub> are replaced by their 0.9<italic>&sgr;</italic> limiting magnitudes if the signal is below that level. Finally, we remove objects whose pseudo-<italic>&chi;</italic><sup>2</sup> is larger than 2.8, with <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${\\chi }^{2}={\\sum }_{i}\\mathrm{SGN}{({f}_{i})({f}_{i}/{\\sigma }_{i})}^{2}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>&chi;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>2</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msup>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&sum;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mi>SGN</mml:mi>\n<mml:msup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>f</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>f</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>2</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn7.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, where the summation runs over all the ACS bands. Here <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> and <italic>&sgr;</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> are the flux density and its uncertainty in the <italic>i</italic>th band image, respectively, and SGN (<italic>f</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>) is the sign function, whose definition is SGN (<italic>x</italic>)&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1 if <italic>x</italic>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;0, SGN (<italic>x</italic>)&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0 if <italic>x</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0, and SGN (<italic>x</italic>)&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;1 if <italic>x</italic>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;0. The selected dropout galaxies are presented in Tables&nbsp;4&ndash;6 in Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>).</p>\n<p>From the Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>) samples, we remove a <italic>Y</italic>-dropout galaxy, HFF6P-1733-6559, and a <italic>YJ</italic>-dropout galaxy, HFF6P-1732-6562, in the Abell 370 parallel field, because they appear to be spurious sources by visual inspection. These are indeed the same object meeting both the <italic>Y</italic>- and <italic>YJ</italic>-dropout selections. As a result, the total numbers of the selected galaxies are 350, 64, and 39 for <italic>i</italic>, <italic>Y</italic>, and <italic>YJ</italic> dropouts, respectively. Their photometric redshift distributions are shown in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff1\">1</xref>. The averages of the reliable (<italic>z</italic> &gt; 4) photometric redshifts of the <italic>i</italic>, <italic>Y</italic>, and <italic>YJ</italic> dropouts are <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;6.2, 7.8, and 8.5, respectively. Therefore, we use <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;6, 8, and 9 in the calculation of the sizes, magnitudes, and magnification factors for <italic>i</italic>, <italic>Y</italic>, and <italic>YJ</italic> dropouts, respectively. Fixing the redshift to these values does not cause any systematic errors in the following results.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff1\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 1.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc1\">\n<p>Normalized distributions of the photometric redshifts of our samples for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 (blue), 8 (green), and 9 (red).</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff1_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff1.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff1_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff1_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff1_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff1_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n</sec>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs3\">\n<label>3.</label>\n<title>Size and Magnitude Measurements</title>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs3-1\">\n<label>3.1.</label>\n<title>Two-dimensional Profile Fitting</title>\n<p>In this subsection, we estimate lensing-corrected, i.e., intrinsic, sizes and magnitudes of the dropout galaxies.</p>\n<p>The lensing effects are calculated using the software <monospace>glafic</monospace> v1.2.7 (Oguri <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib83\">2010</xref>). For the mass distributions of Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403, we use our version 4 mass models updated to reflect the latest MUSE observations by Mahler et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib73\">2018</xref>) and Caminha et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib22\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>), respectively. For MACS J0717.5&plus;3745 and MACS J1149.6&plus;2223, we use our version 3 mass models constructed in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">K16</xref>. For Abell S1063 and Abell 370, we newly construct version 4 mass models following the method established in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">K16</xref>. Modeling details about the four version 4 mass models are described in Appendix <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfapp1\">A</xref>. All of the mass models are available on the Space Telescope Science Institute website.<xref ref-type=\"fn\" rid=\"apjaaa6cffn2\"><sup>8</sup></xref>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cffn2\">\n<label><sup>8</sup></label>\n<p>\n<ext-link ext-link-type=\"uri\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"https://archive.stsci.edu/prepds/frontier/lensmodels/\">https://archive.stsci.edu/prepds/frontier/lensmodels/</ext-link>\n</p>\n</fn> The uncertainty in each magnification factor is calculated from 10,000 models sampled from a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) chain (see Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs3-2\">3.2</xref>). This uncertainty is smaller than the scatter in magnification factors among all modeling teams&rsquo; models. The typical scatters are 30&percnt; at <italic>&mgr;</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;2 and 70&percnt; at <italic>&mgr;</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;40 as reported in Priewe et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib93\">2017</xref>), who conducted a thorough comparison between the mass maps of Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403 by all modeling teams (see also Meneghetti et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib75\">2017</xref>). The smaller uncertainties in our models are due to limited flexibilities inherent in parametric modeling methods, while the predicted magnification factors are consistent with those by the other teams (see Figures&nbsp;10&ndash;11 and 12&ndash;13 in Priewe et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib93\">2017</xref>).</p>\n<p>The method to measure intrinsic sizes and magnitudes is identical to that in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>. However, while the measurements in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> were conducted only for bright galaxies, here we deal with all the galaxies in the samples. We fit a S&eacute;rsic profile to a galaxy image in an 8&farcs;4&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;8&farcs;4 cutout image using a two-dimensional fitting algorithm conducted by the command <monospace>optimize</monospace> in <monospace>glafic</monospace>, which simultaneously corrects for the lensing and point-spread function (PSF) effects. In order to correct for the lensing effects, an ellipsoidal S&eacute;rsic profile on the source plane is lensed onto the image plane, and the galaxy image is fitted with the lensing-distorted S&eacute;rsic profile. In order to correct for the PSF effects, the lensing-distorted S&eacute;rsic profile is convolved with an average stellar image on the image plane, which is generated by stacking 5&ndash;20 stars found in each field. The S&eacute;rsic profile is defined as<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn11\">\n<label>11</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{\\rm{\\Sigma }}(r)={{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{0}\\exp \\left[-{b}_{n}{\\left(\\displaystyle \\frac{r}{{r}_{{\\rm{e}}}}\\right)}^{1/n}\\right],\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&Sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&Sgr;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mfenced separators=\"\" open=\"[\" close=\"]\">\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>b</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>n</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:msup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mfenced separators=\"\" open=\"(\" close=\")\">\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mstyle displaystyle=\"true\">\n<mml:mfrac>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mfrac>\n</mml:mstyle>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mfenced>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1</mml:mn>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>n</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msup>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mfenced>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn11.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>where &Sgr;(<italic>r</italic>), &Sgr;<sub>0</sub>, <italic>b</italic><sub><italic>n</italic></sub>, <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>, and <italic>n</italic> represent the surface brightness profile, surface brightness at <italic>r</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0, parameter to convert the scale radius to the half-light radius, half-light radius, and S&eacute;rsic index, respectively. The ellipticity <italic>e</italic> and position angle are introduced by a simple variable transformation (see Oguri <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib83\">2010</xref> for details). In what follows, <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub> means the circularized half-light radius, <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{\\mathrm{maj}}\\sqrt{1-e}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>maj</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n<mml:msqrt>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msqrt>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn8.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, where <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{\\mathrm{maj}}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>maj</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn9.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> is the radius along the major axis. The magnitude is calculated from <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub> and &Sgr;<sub>0</sub>. During the fitting, the S&eacute;rsic index is fixed to <italic>n</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1, and the maximum ellipticity is set to 0.9. A uniform sky background is assumed, and the normalization is optimized at the same time. When nearby objects may introduce any bias to the fitting result, we mask these objects or add additional profiles to fit the nearby objects simultaneously. The fittings are conducted using the <italic>YJJH</italic>, <italic>JJHH</italic>, and <italic>JHH</italic> combined images at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively. Although we have already constructed size samples in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> from the Abell 2744 cluster and parallel fields, we conduct the fittings again because there are updates on the mass map of the cluster. The obtained morphological properties and magnitudes are presented in tables in Appendix <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfapp2\">B</xref>. The fitting results for galaxies fainter than &minus;18 mag are also graphically shown in figures in Appendix <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfapp2\">B</xref>.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs3-2\">\n<label>3.2.</label>\n<title>Error Estimations</title>\n<p>In this subsection, we evaluate errors in the measured sizes and magnitudes following the method in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>, but in a more efficient way. We consider two sources of errors: errors in the fitting procedure and errors in the mass map.</p>\n<p>There are two types of errors in the fitting procedure. One is a systematic bias, by which the sizes and magnitudes of larger (smaller) galaxies are underestimated (overestimated). The other is a random error, which arises from random sky noise that disperses the estimated size and magnitude. In order to estimate these errors, we conduct Monte Carlo simulations, in which we bury simulated galaxies in a real image and perform the same fitting procedure as for real dropout galaxies. Since these systematic and random errors are primarily dependent on the galaxy apparent magnitude, apparent radius, and sky value in the vicinity, we estimate the two errors as a function of the three parameters. We use the Abell 2744 cluster field image for this derivation and apply the relation to all 12 fields. In detail, first, we select a random position in the image and bury an <italic>n</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1 S&eacute;rsic profile, whose magnitude, radius, ellipticity, and position angle are chosen randomly. Second, we conduct the same procedure on this pseudo-galaxy as for real galaxies. We repeat these two processes until we obtain a sufficient number of measurements in each parameter bin. Third, for each real dropout galaxy, we choose a set of simulated galaxies whose apparent magnitudes, apparent radii, and sky values in the vicinity are close to those of the dropout galaxy. Using the intrinsic magnitudes and radii of the simulated galaxies in this set, we estimate the random errors and correct for the systematic errors in size and magnitude. Examples of the Monte Carlo simulations are presented in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff2\">2</xref>.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff2\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 2.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc2\">\n<p>Examples of the Monte Carlo simulations to estimate the systematic and random errors in size and magnitude measurements. The top panel shows the median and 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> distribution of output radii as a function of input radius for galaxies with an apparent magnitude of <italic>m</italic>/mag&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;26.7&ndash;27.7 and for a sky value of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\overline{{n}_{\\mathrm{sky}}}/\\mathrm{count}=0.001\\mbox{--}0.003$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mover accent=\"true\">\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>n</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>sky</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&macr;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mover>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>count</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.001</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&ndash;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.003</mml:mn>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn10.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. The bottom panel shows the median and 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> distribution of output magnitudes as a function of input magnitude for galaxies with <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>/kpc&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.46&ndash;0.69 and for a sky value of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\overline{{n}_{\\mathrm{sky}}}/\\mathrm{count}\\,=0.001\\mbox{--}0.003$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mover accent=\"true\">\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>n</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>sky</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&macr;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mover>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>count</mml:mi>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.001</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&ndash;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.003</mml:mn>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn11.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff2_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff2.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff2_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff2_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff2_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff2_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>Systematic errors in mass maps also affect measurement results. Since the apparent magnitudes and sizes of lensed galaxies are converted into intrinsic values using mass maps, an overestimate of the magnification factor results in an underestimate of the intrinsic sizes and magnitudes, and vice versa. In order to estimate the errors in magnification, we generate an MCMC chain of the mass model parameters using the command <monospace>mcmc</monospace> in <monospace>glafic</monospace>. From 10,000 samples in the chain, we estimate the error in magnification factor at the positions of each dropout galaxy with the <monospace>mcmc</monospace>_<monospace>calcim</monospace> command. For each cluster, 100 mass maps generated from randomly selected MCMC samples are available on the Space Telescope Science Institute website.</p>\n<p>The random errors in size and magnitude due to the fitting procedure and random errors in magnification factor are presented in tables in Appendix <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfapp2\">B</xref>.</p>\n</sec>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs4\">\n<label>4.</label>\n<title>Size&ndash;Luminosity Distributions at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9</title>\n<p>In this section, we first present the distribution of our galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane. Then, detection incompleteness is calculated as a function of absolute magnitude and size for each field and redshift range. Finally, we use these incompleteness maps on the size&ndash;luminosity plane to simultaneously derive intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relations and luminosity functions for the first time at these redshift ranges.</p>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs4-1\">\n<label>4.1.</label>\n<title>Galaxy Distribution on the Size&ndash;Luminosity Plane</title>\n<p>Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff3\">3</xref> shows the size&ndash;luminosity distributions of our galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, together with those from previous studies that adopt two-dimensional profile fittings in size measurements. The error bars include the errors in the fitting process and our mass maps. Our samples occupy either the same regions as the previous samples or their reasonable extrapolations toward much fainter magnitudes.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff3\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 3.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc3\">\n<p>Galaxy distributions on the size&ndash;luminosity plane at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 (top), 8 (middle), and 9 (bottom). The red and blue points represent our galaxies from the cluster fields and parallel fields, respectively. The green points represent galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 and 8 in Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>; top and middle, respectively) and at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9 in Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>; bottom).</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff3_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff3.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff3_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff3_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff3_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff3_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>As summarized in tables in Appendix <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfapp2\">B</xref>, some galaxies are multiply imaged on the image plane. The physical parameters of these galaxies are calculated by averaging over the multiple images. The numbers of independent galaxies with size measurements are thus reduced to 334, 61, and 37 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively. Among them, the numbers of faint (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &gsim; &minus;18) galaxies are 83, 6, and 3, respectively. These numbers should be compared only with those from previous studies that adopt parametric size measurements such as <monospace>GALFIT</monospace> (Peng et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib89\">2002</xref>, <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib90\">2010</xref>), not with those based on nonparametric methods such as &ldquo;curve-of-growth.&rdquo; This is because these two methods rely on different assumptions, which may introduce different biases and therefore make comparisons of the results difficult. At faint magnitude ranges, as investigated in this work, previous studies that adopt parametric size measurements are Ono et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib86\">2013</xref>), <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>, Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>), Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>), and Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) (see also Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>). The number of galaxies in our samples and in the previous studies are presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft1\">1</xref>. For <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 and 9, the addition of our samples increases the number of faint (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &gsim; &minus;18) galaxies with size measurements about 2.5 and 4 times, respectively. For <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8, our sample is the first that contains faint galaxies with size measurements. The faintest objects among the previous samples have <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;&minus;14.48 (Bouwens et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>), &minus;18.1 (Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>), and &minus;17.8 (Holwerda et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively. We push the faint limits down to <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;&minus;12.3, &minus;16.8, and &minus;15.4 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively.</p>\n<table-wrap id=\"apjaaa6cft1\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Table 1</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cftc1\">\n<p>Number of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;&minus;18 Galaxies in the Present and Previous Samples</p>\n</caption>\n<table>\n<colgroup>\n<col align=\"left\"/>\n<col align=\"center\"/>\n<col align=\"center\"/>\n<col align=\"center\"/>\n<col align=\"left\"/>\n</colgroup>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th align=\"left\">References</th>\n<th align=\"center\"><italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7</th>\n<th align=\"center\"><italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8</th>\n<th align=\"center\"><italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9</th>\n<th align=\"left\">Data</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">This work</td>\n<td align=\"center\">91 (350)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">7 (64)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">3 (39)</td>\n<td align=\"left\">Six HFF cluster and parallel fields</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Ono et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib86\">2013</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">0 (9)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">0 (6)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"left\">HUDF12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"center\">1 (8)</td>\n<td align=\"left\">XDF and CANDELS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">4 (31)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">0 (8)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"left\">First HFF cluster and parallel fields</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">7&nbsp;&plus;&nbsp;1 (422 &plus; 173)<xref ref-type=\"fn\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft1fna\"><sup>a</sup></xref>\n</td>\n<td align=\"center\">0 (46)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"left\">CANDELS, HUDF09/12, and first two HFF parallel fields</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">47 (76)</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"center\">&hellip;</td>\n<td align=\"left\">First two HFF cluster fields</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft1_tb.gif\"/>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft1_lr.gif\">\n<caption>\n<p>Typeset image</p>\n</caption>\n</graphic>\n<table-wrap-foot>\n<p><bold>Note.</bold> The number of galaxies in the full sample is shown in parentheses.</p>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cft1fna\">\n<label><sup>a</sup></label>\n<p>Numbers at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6 and 7 are presented.</p>\n</fn>\n</table-wrap-foot>\n</table-wrap>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs4-2\">\n<label>4.2.</label>\n<title>Completeness Estimation</title>\n<p>For a given total magnitude, galaxies with larger sizes are less likely to be detected in observations because of their low surface brightnesses. Since this effect is more prominent for fainter objects, observed size&ndash;luminosity relations can become significantly steeper than intrinsic ones. We conduct the following Monte Carlo simulations to calculate detection completeness as a function of absolute magnitude and size. The detection completeness is defined as the fraction of galaxies that are detected and pass the dropout selection described in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs2-2\">2.2</xref>. (1) We select random positions uniformly on the source plane. (2) For each position, we generate an artificial galaxy with a certain size and magnitude and place it, taking the lensing and PSF effects into account, into the combined image, which is used as the detection image in the catalog construction. The galaxy is modeled with a S&eacute;rsic profile of the index <italic>n</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1. The ellipticity is randomly chosen from a uniform distribution between 0 and 0.9. (3) We run <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> on the image with artificial galaxies and calculate the fraction of artificial galaxies that are detected by <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> and bright enough to meet the criteria of dropout selection. (4) We repeat steps (1)&ndash;(3), changing the size and magnitude of artificial galaxies. It should be noted that we do not assume any specific spectral energy distribution (SED) shape. This is because, primarily, the completeness is not dependent on the SED shape but only on size and magnitude. As an example, the obtained completeness maps at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 in the Abell 2744 cluster and parallel fields are shown in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff4\">4</xref>. Note that although faint galaxies are bright enough to be detected if highly magnified, their completeness is significantly low because they rarely fall onto highly magnified regions.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff4\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 4.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc4\">\n<p>Detection completeness at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 as a function of absolute magnitude and size for the Abell 2744 cluster (top) and parallel (bottom) fields, shown on a logarithmic scale. Galaxies detected in each field are plotted with squares.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff4_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff4.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff4_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff4_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff4_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff4_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>As seen in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff5\">5</xref>, the observed size&ndash;luminosity distributions can be significantly deformed by incompleteness, which depends on size and luminosity. We discuss the impact of incompleteness on the estimation of the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relations in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-1\">5.1</xref>. In the cluster fields, even galaxies fainter than &sim;&minus;18 mag are detected, but with low completeness. For example, at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;16, only those with <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;0.1 kpc are included in the samples. This means that while the HFF has opened a window to faint galaxies, it is open only to very small objects. On the other hand, galaxies detected in the parallel fields are limited to &sim;&minus;18 mag, but with a relatively high completeness over a wide size range because completeness drops sharply at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;18. Therefore, the cluster fields require a more careful consideration of incompleteness effects.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff5\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 5.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc5\">\n<p>Bivariate probability distributions of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane shown on a logarithmic scale. The top panel shows the intrinsic distribution with an arbitrary normalization. The contour levels are logarithmically equidistant with 1 dex steps. The middle and bottom panels are for the observed distributions in the Abell 2744 cluster and parallel fields, respectively, calculated by multiplying the intrinsic distribution by the completeness map for each field. Galaxies detected in each field are shown with squares in the lower two panels. The parameters of the intrinsic bivariate distribution presented here are the best-fit parameters obtained in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs4-3\">4.3</xref>.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff5_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff5.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff5_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff5_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff5_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff5_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs4-3\">\n<label>4.3.</label>\n<title>Maximum-likelihood Estimation of the Intrinsic Size&ndash;Luminosity Distribution</title>\n<p>In this subsection, we obtain for each of the three redshift ranges the incompleteness-corrected or intrinsic bivariate size&ndash;luminosity distribution of galaxies, which is a product of the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation and the luminosity function. We model the size&ndash;luminosity relation by a log-normal distribution with three free parameters while modeling the luminosity function by a Schechter function with two free parameters; the total number of free parameters is thus five. Then, by multiplying the intrinsic distribution by the incompleteness map, we model the observed size&ndash;luminosity distribution of galaxies. Maximum-likelihood estimation (MLE) is used to obtain the best-fit values of these parameters that best reproduce the observed bivariate distribution.</p>\n<p>This bivariate method has been exploited in de Jong &amp; Lacey (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib31\">2000</xref>) and Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) to simultaneously derive the size&ndash;luminosity relation and UV luminosity function for local spiral galaxies and LBGs at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;5, respectively. A similar method has also been adopted in Schmidt et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib101a\">2014b</xref>). This method has two advantages over binning methods conventionally adopted as described in Schmidt et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib101a\">2014b</xref>); one is that no information is lost because data are not binned, and the other is that photometric errors in magnitude are also considered. In addition, by determining the size&ndash;luminosity relation and luminosity function simultaneously, we are able to evaluate the degeneracy between those two relations. Furthermore, in most previous studies, size&ndash;luminosity relations have been determined to minimize the residuals in size, which is equivalent to MLE that assumes observed galaxies have a flat distribution in luminosity. On the other hand, our method correctly derives the size&ndash;luminosity relation and, consequently, the luminosity function because the luminosity distribution is also modeled using luminosity functions.</p>\n<p>The probability density function (PDF) of the intrinsic galaxy distribution on the size&ndash;luminosity plane &PSgr;(<italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>, <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>) is modeled as<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn12\">\n<label>12</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{\\rm{\\Psi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&delta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn14.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> is a Gaussian function whose peak is at the observed size and magnitude (<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${r}_{{\\rm{e}},j},{M}_{\\mathrm{UV},j}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow/>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow/>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn15.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>), and the variances are equal to their observed errors (<italic>&delta;r</italic><sub>e,j</sub>, <italic>&delta;</italic> <italic>M</italic><sub>UV,j</sub>). The likelihood in the <italic>i</italic>th field <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${{ \\mathcal L }}_{i}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#x0E238;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn16.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> is given by<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn18\">\n<label>18</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{{ \\mathcal L }}_{i}({r}_{0},\\sigma ,\\beta ,{M}^{* },\\alpha )=\\displaystyle \\prod _{j}{f}_{i,j}({r}_{0},\\sigma ,\\beta ,{M}^{* },\\alpha ).\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#x0E238;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:msup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&ast;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msup>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:munder>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mstyle displaystyle=\"true\">\n<mml:mo>&prod;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mstyle>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:munder>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>f</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:msup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&ast;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msup>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>.</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn18.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>The total likelihood <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${ \\mathcal L }$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#x0E238;</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn17.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> is the product of the likelihood in each field,<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn19\">\n<label>19</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{ \\mathcal L }\\equiv \\displaystyle \\prod _{i}{{ \\mathcal L }}_{i}.\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#x0E238;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&Congruent;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:munder>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mstyle displaystyle=\"true\">\n<mml:mo>&prod;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mstyle>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:munder>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#x0E238;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mi>.</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn19.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>\n</p>\n<p>We use the MCMC procedure to estimate the best-fit values and uncertainties for the five parameters and the degeneracy between them. We assume flat priors on all five parameters. Note that we do not use the galaxies HFF5P-1940-3315 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 and HFF5P-2129-2064 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 in the Abell S1063 parallel field because they are outliers. For the MCMC sampling, we use the public software <monospace>emcee</monospace> (Foreman-Mackey et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib41\">2013</xref>). The MCMC results are shown in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft2\">2</xref> and Figures <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff6\">6</xref>&ndash;<xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff8\">8</xref>. As an example, the obtained intrinsic bivariate size&ndash;luminosity distribution at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 is presented in the top panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff5\">5</xref>.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff6\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 6.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc6\">\n<p>Two-dimensional projections of the MCMC samples at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. The inner and outer contours represent 68&percnt; and 95&percnt; confidence intervals. The three vertical dashed lines on the histograms show the 16th, 50th, and 84th percentiles. Plotted using the <monospace>corner.py</monospace> module (Foreman-Mackey <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib40\">2016</xref>).</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff6_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff6.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff6_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff6_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff6_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff6_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff7\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 7.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc7\">\n<p>Same as Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff6\">6</xref> but for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff7_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff7.eps\"/>\n<graphic -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn55a.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>\n</td>\n<td align=\"center\">\n<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $-{2.22}_{-0.17}^{+0.26}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>2.22</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.17</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.26</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn56a.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft2_tb.gif\"/>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft2_lr.gif\">\n<caption>\n<p>Typeset image</p>\n</caption>\n</graphic>\n<table-wrap-foot>\n<p><bold>Notes.</bold> Numbers in square brackets are fixed during the fitting.</p>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cft2fna\">\n<label><sup>a</sup></label>\n<p>Size&ndash;luminosity relation is presented in their Appendix D.</p>\n</fn>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cft2fnb\">\n<label><sup>b</sup></label>\n<p>Effective slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation, although its parameterization is different from ours.</p>\n</fn>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cft2fnc\">\n<label><sup>c</sup></label>\n<p>Size&ndash;luminosity relation is presented in their paper and the bottom panel of our Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff12\">12</xref>.</p>\n</fn>\n</table-wrap-foot>\n</table-wrap>\n</sec>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs5\">\n<label>5.</label>\n<title>Discussion</title>\n<p>In this section, we first discuss the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relations and luminosity functions at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9. Second, we construct a model to reproduce the steep size&ndash;luminosity relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 using the result of the abundance matching in Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>). Third, we show that there are large uncertainties in the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;6 luminosity functions derived in previous studies because of a large variance in the assumed size&ndash;luminosity relations and that those uncertainties are greatly reduced at least for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 by using the size&ndash;luminosity relation obtained in this work. Finally, we discuss the redshift evolution of size.</p>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs5-1\">\n<label>5.1.</label>\n<title>The Intrinsic Size&ndash;Luminosity Relation and Luminosity Function at z&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7</title>\n<p>We discuss here the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation and UV luminosity function at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, which are reliably estimated because of the large sample. The best-fit size&ndash;luminosity relation and its 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> uncertainty are presented in the top panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff9\">9</xref>, together with the results of previous work.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff9\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 9.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc9\">\n<p>Galaxy distributions on the size&ndash;luminosity plane at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 (top), 8 (middle), and 9 (bottom). The red and green points represent, respectively, our galaxies and those from previous studies (Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref> for <italic>z</italic> &sim; 6&ndash;7 and 8; Holwerda et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref> for <italic>z</italic> &sim; 9). The red and blue solid lines represent the size&ndash;luminosity relations by the completeness-corrected and completeness-uncorrected fittings to our samples, respectively. The 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> distribution of the completeness-corrected size&ndash;luminosity relation is shown by the red shaded region. While the green solid lines show the best-fit power laws obtained by Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) and Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>), the orange solid line is for the result obtained by Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) based on two-dimensional size measurements.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff9_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff9.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff9_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff9_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff9_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff9_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>First, to evaluate the impact of detection incompleteness on the estimation of the size&ndash;luminosity relation, we fit the apparent size&ndash;luminosity distribution without correcting for completeness. In this process, as an alternative to <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${{\\rm{\\Psi }}}_{i}^{{\\prime} }$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&PSgr;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>i</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo accent=\"true\">&prime;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn71.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> in Equation (<xref ref-type=\"disp-formula\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfeqn16\">16</xref>), we use a distribution model of<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn20\">\n<label>20</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{{\\rm{\\Psi }}}_{\\mathrm{apparent}}({r}_{{\\rm{e}}},{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}};{r}_{0},\\sigma ,\\beta )\\\\ \\quad =\\,P({r}_{{\\rm{e}}},{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}};{r}_{0},\\sigma ,\\beta ),\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mtable>\n<mml:mtr>\n<mml:mtd columnalign=\"left\">\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi
