mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mtd>\n</mml:mtr>\n<mml:mtr>\n<mml:mtd columnalign=\"left\">\n<mml:mspace width=\"1.0em\"/>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mi>P</mml:mi>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n</mml:mtd>\n</mml:mtr>\n</mml:mtable>\n</mml:math> -->\n<graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn20.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>where <italic>P</italic>(<italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>, <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>) is described in Equation (<xref ref-type=\"disp-formula\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfeqn13\">13</xref>). This implies that we assume a flat distribution for the magnitude distribution. The best-fit parameter sets estimated using MLE are presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft2\">2</xref> as &ldquo;This work (apparent).&rdquo; We find that the modal sizes are &sim;0.15 dex underestimated, on average, and as large as &sim;0.2 dex at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;16. The slope of the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation is overestimated by &Delta;<italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.06. This suggests that incompleteness has a slight contribution to the apparent steepness. In contrast, we find that the variance of the size&ndash;luminosity relation <italic>&sgr;</italic> is &sim;25&percnt; underestimated if incompleteness is not corrected for.</p>\n<p>Then, we discuss the incompleteness-corrected results. Concerning the size&ndash;luminosity relation, the marginalized value of the slope is <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta ={0.46}_{-0.09}^{+0.08}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.46</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.09</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.08</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn72.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. This slope is steeper than <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta \\,={0.25}_{-0.14}^{+0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.14</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn73.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;5 by Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>; with incompleteness correction) and <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta ={0.25}_{-0.05}^{+0.05}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.05</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.05</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn74.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6 by Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>; without incompleteness correction), both of them utilizing brighter (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;18) samples. This is the first time to confirm the steepness of the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 galaxies. Although a steep slope for galaxies at this redshift range was first reported by <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> based on reliable size measurements of the first HFF sample and then confirmed with larger samples by Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib14\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017c</xref>), none of these studies has applied incompleteness correction. The differences in the slope from Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) and Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) can be due to the differences in the magnitude range and hence in the physics dominating in galaxies. We further investigate this physical origin of the steepness in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-3\">5.3</xref> using the result of the abundance matching by Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>). As described in the next paragraph, the difference from Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) can also be explained by the differences in methods to measure magnitudes and to fit the size&ndash;luminosity relation. We note that although it has a steep slope, the best-fit intrinsic bivariate distribution predicts the existence of faint galaxies with large sizes, for instance, <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;16 galaxies with <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;1 kpc (see the top panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff5\">5</xref>).</p>\n<p>Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) found remarkably shallower slopes of <italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.25&nbsp;&PlusMinus;&nbsp;0.05 for brighter galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6 and 7 even without correcting for incompleteness. Interestingly, in Figures <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff3\">3</xref>&nbsp;and <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff9\">9</xref>, their galaxies appear to have a similar slope to ours. In fact, while their samples made public and plotted here use <monospace>GALFIT</monospace> magnitudes, they have used <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> magnitudes to derive the slope (T. Shibuya 2017, private communication). Applying the same method (Equation (<xref ref-type=\"disp-formula\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfeqn20\">20</xref>)) to their sample, we find that using <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> magnitudes gives slopes 0.13 and 0.21 shallower than those based on <monospace>GALFIT</monospace> magnitudes at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6 and 7, respectively. This may suggest that using <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> magnitudes leads them to derive the shallower slopes. In addition, our fitting method is different from theirs. They use a least-squares method that minimizes residuals only in size, which can bias the slope toward shallower values.</p>\n<p>The modal size at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21 is <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${0.94}_{-0.15}^{+0.20}\\,\\mathrm{kpc}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.94</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.15</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.20</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mi>kpc</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn75.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. This size can be slightly larger than the incompleteness-uncorrected sizes by the previous studies (Bouwens et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib10\">2004</xref>; Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>; Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>). We note that the sizes in Bouwens et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib10\">2004</xref>) and Oesch et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>) are averages in the range of &minus;21&nbsp;&le;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&le;&nbsp;&minus;19.7, which means the sizes at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21 should be larger (see also Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff15\">15</xref>).</p>\n<p>The variance of the log-normal size distribution is <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\sigma \\,={0.87}_{-0.09}^{+0.10}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.87</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.09</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.10</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn76.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. This is in good accordance with the values of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\sigma ={0.83}_{-0.044}^{+0.046}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.83</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.044</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.046</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn77.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> and <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${0.90}_{-0.065}^{+0.15}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.90</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.065</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.15</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn78.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4 and 5, respectively, in Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>). According to the analytical model by Mo et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib77\">1998</xref>; see also Fall &amp; Efstathiou <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib37\">1980</xref>), galaxy sizes are basically proportional to their halo sizes and spin parameters. The distribution of the spin parameter is log-normal at a fixed halo mass and thus also approximately log-normal at a fixed luminosity. Its variance was estimated to be <italic>&sgr;</italic><sub>h</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.60 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0 and revealed to scarcely evolve toward higher redshifts by Zjupa &amp; Springel (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib114\">2017</xref>) with the dark matter&ndash;only Illustris simulation. Since the observed variance of the galaxy-size distribution is larger than that of the spin parameter, there may be some elements that broaden the galaxy-size distribution. For example, a scatter in halo mass at fixed luminosity would result in a broader size distribution. This scatter was recently suggested at low redshifts in Charlton et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib25\">2017</xref>). Another explanation is a disk-to-halo ratio of specific angular momentum depending on the spin parameter, which means the galaxy size is no longer proportional to the spin parameter. We note that the derived variance <italic>&sgr;</italic> has been corrected for errors in size and magnitude measurements as described in Equation (<xref ref-type=\"disp-formula\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfeqn17\">17</xref>).</p>\n<p>We find a shallow faint-end slope of the luminosity function of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\alpha =-{1.86}_{-0.18}^{+0.17}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.86</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.18</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.17</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn79.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, consistent with the slopes in Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib11\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib13\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017b</xref>) and Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>) but slightly incompatible with recently suggested steep slopes of <italic>&agr;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq; &minus;2.00 to &minus;2.15 (e.g., Ishigaki et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>; Livermore et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib70\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref> ). The reason for this is that our size&ndash;luminosity relation is steeper than those utilized in the previous studies. With a steeper size&ndash;luminosity relation, galaxies are easier to detect, and a smaller amount of incompleteness correction is needed in luminosity function derivation, especially at faint magnitude ranges. Thus, the faint-end slope becomes shallower. The effects of the size&ndash;luminosity relation on the luminosity function are further discussed in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-4\">5.4</xref>.</p>\n<p>The characteristic magnitude, <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${M}^{* }=-{20.73}_{-0.81}^{+0.46}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&ast;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msup>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>20.73</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.81</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.46</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn80.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, is consistent with those of previous work. Since the marginalized distribution has a long tail toward the brighter magnitude, the mode of it is slightly larger, <italic>M</italic>&ast;&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;&minus;20.56. The uncertainty in <italic>M</italic>&ast; is relatively large, probably because we do not use bright-galaxy samples from large-area surveys.</p>\n<p>The parameters of the size&ndash;luminosity relation strongly correlate with those of the luminosity function. The most important may be the correlation between <italic>&agr;</italic> and <italic>&beta;</italic>, which has been pointed out by several works, including Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib45\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2011</xref>) and Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib13\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017b</xref>). The top panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff10\">10</xref> shows the correlation between <italic>&agr;</italic> and <italic>&beta;</italic> obtained in this work together with the previous measurements of these parameters presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft2\">2</xref>. We find that the steeper <italic>&agr;</italic> in Atek et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib2\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015a</xref>) and Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>) will become further consistent with ours if steeper size&ndash;luminosity relations are assumed. Even with our large and deep sample, at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 there still remains a moderate uncertainty in <italic>&agr;</italic> due to the uncertainty in the size&ndash;luminosity relation. This uncertainty in <italic>&agr;</italic> is propagated to the UV luminosity density, a key quantity to calculating the number density of ionizing photons, although no previous studies on cosmic reionization have considered this uncertainty. We note that although the values of <italic>&agr;</italic> obtained in Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>) and Livermore et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib70\">2017</xref>) are consistent with our value, their <italic>&agr;</italic>&ndash;<italic>&beta;</italic> combinations are outside (with a large margin) of the 95&percnt; confidence ellipse obtained in this study. This demonstrates that these parameters must not be determined independently.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff10\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 10.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc10\">\n<p>Correlations between the faint-end slope of the luminosity function, <italic>&agr;</italic>, and the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation, <italic>&beta;</italic>, overplotted with the observational results presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft2\">2</xref> (filled squares) and simulation results (open squares). The top, middle, and bottom panels show the results at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff10_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff10.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff10_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff10_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff10_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff10_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>We also compare our <italic>&agr;</italic> and <italic>&beta;</italic> measurements with the results of the semi-analytical model of galaxy formation <sc>L-Galaxies</sc> (Henriques et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib49\">2015</xref>). We run the <sc>L-Galaxies</sc> code on two <italic>N</italic>-body dark matter simulations of different resolutions, the Millennium (Springel et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib105\">2005</xref>) and Millennium-II (Boylan-Kolchin et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib16\">2009</xref>), and combine the two galaxy catalogs to probe a wide halo mass range. Applying Equation (<xref ref-type=\"disp-formula\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfeqn12\">12</xref>) to the combined catalog finds that <sc>L-Galaxies</sc> predicts an <italic>&agr;</italic> consistent with our value but a significantly flatter <italic>&beta;</italic>. Results of the semi-analytical model of galaxy formation <sc>meraxes</sc> (Mutch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib79\">2016</xref>; Liu et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib69\">2017</xref>) are also compared. We find a good agreement with our results for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 and 8 and an acceptable agreement for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9. Note that the values of <italic>&beta;</italic> obtained here are different from those obtained in Liu et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib69\">2017</xref>) because of different fitting methods.</p>\n<p>However, we find that the two models tend to predict relatively flatter size&ndash;luminosity relations, especially at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 and 9. Their sizes are calculated essentially based on the analytical model by Mo et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib77\">1998</xref>). The flatter size&ndash;luminosity relations than observed may suggest the importance of careful calculations of the exchange of angular momentum between the dark matter halo and the stellar disk. Indeed, <sc>meraxes</sc> assumes a constant specific angular momentum of <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1, which disagrees with our result in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-3\">5.3</xref>. In <sc>L-Galaxies</sc>, specific angular momenta are calculated and compared with those by other semi-analytical models and hydrodynamical simulations (e.g., Guo et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib48\">2016</xref>; Hou et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib52\">2018</xref>). However, we do not discuss their results because they provide only the specific angular momenta of cooled gas, which may be systematically different from the specific angular momenta of disks, <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>. Further comparison between the observations and simulations is beyond the scope of this paper.</p>\n<p>Another parameter set that shows a strong correlation is <italic>&agr;</italic> and <italic>M</italic>&ast;, as seen in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff6\">6</xref> and as has been reported in previous studies. We confirm that the uncertainty in <italic>&agr;</italic> decreases from &sim;0.2 to &lsim;0.1 if <italic>M</italic>&ast; is virtually fixed to, for instance, <italic>M</italic>&ast;&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21. The slope <italic>&beta;</italic> also correlates with the modal size <italic>r</italic><sub>0</sub> and weakly with the width of the size distribution <italic>&sgr;</italic>; both correlations originate from a requirement to reproduce small faint galaxies (except for the <italic>&beta;</italic>&ndash;<italic>&sgr;</italic> correlation at <italic>z</italic> &sim; 9).</p>\n<p>Since <italic>&agr;</italic> strongly correlates with <italic>M</italic>&ast; and <italic>&beta;</italic>, a more accurate measurement of <italic>&agr;</italic> requires a larger sample containing bright objects (to better constrain <italic>M</italic>&ast;) accompanied by a completeness estimation on the size&ndash;luminosity plane (to obtain an unbiased <italic>&beta;</italic> value).</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs5-2\">\n<label>5.2.</label>\n<title>The Intrinsic Size&ndash;Luminosity Relation and Luminosity Function at z&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9</title>\n<p>The fitting results of the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity distributions at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9 are presented in the middle and bottom panels of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff9\">9</xref>, respectively. Since the samples are smaller than that at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, the uncertainties in the parameters are typically &gsim;2&ndash;3 times larger.</p>\n<p>Similar to that at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, we find steep slopes of the size&ndash;luminosity relations of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta ={0.38}_{-0.78}^{+0.28}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.38</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.78</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.28</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn81.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> and <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${0.56}_{-0.27}^{+1.01}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.56</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.27</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.01</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn82.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9, respectively. These are steeper than the slope of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta \\,={0.19}_{-0.25}^{+0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.19</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn83.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 by Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>), although the differences are within the 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> errors. However, the distributions of our galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane appear to be consistent with theirs, as is the case for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7.</p>\n<p>The modal sizes at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21 are <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${0.81}_{-0.26}^{+5.28}\\,$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.81</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.26</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>5.28</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mrow/>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn84.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> and <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${1.20}_{-0.74}^{+367.64}\\,\\mathrm{kpc}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.20</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.74</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>367.64</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mspace width=\"0.25em\"/>\n<mml:mi>kpc</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn85.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9, respectively. If incompleteness is not corrected for, the sizes become 0.2&ndash;0.3 dex smaller at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9, a slightly larger amount of decrease than that at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. These are consistent with the incompleteness-uncorrected sizes of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${r}_{{\\rm{e}}}={0.419}_{-0.262}^{+1.981}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.419</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.262</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.981</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn86.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 by Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) and <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${r}_{{\\rm{e}}}={0.6}_{-0.3}^{+0.3}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.6</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.3</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.3</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn87.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9 by Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>).</p>\n<p>The variance of the size distribution <italic>&sgr;</italic> is <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${0.80}_{-0.26}^{+1.07}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.80</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.26</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.07</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn88.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> and <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${1.04}_{-0.46}^{+1.52}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.04</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.46</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.52</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn89.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9, respectively, being almost constant at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9. While we do not find any indication of the evolution of <italic>&sgr;</italic> over this redshift range, the modal value of the variance distribution may decrease with redshift. Further discussion needs larger samples.</p>\n<p>While the faint-end slope of the luminosity function at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9 is relatively shallow (<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\alpha =-{1.64}_{-0.28}^{+0.61}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.64</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.28</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.61</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn90.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>), that at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 may be steep (<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\alpha =-{2.26}_{-0.99}^{+0.49}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>2.26</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.99</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.49</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn91.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>). However, both values are consistent with the value at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 due to the large uncertainties.</p>\n<p>At <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8&ndash;9, the probability distributions of <italic>M</italic>&ast; have tails toward the brighter magnitudes, and thus the median values are remarkably brighter than that at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. This is because our samples do not have enough bright galaxies due to the small cosmic volume the HFF program is probing. We note that the <italic>M</italic>&ast; values at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8&ndash;9 are close to typical magnitudes at these redshifts of <italic>M</italic>&ast;&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;21 within the uncertainties. Furthermore, the modes are <italic>M</italic>&ast;&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;19.95 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and &minus;19.80 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9.</p>\n<p>We also calculate <italic>r</italic><sub>0</sub>, <italic>&sgr;</italic>, <italic>&beta;</italic>, and <italic>&agr;</italic> by fixing <italic>M</italic>&ast; to &minus;20.73, the best-fit value at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, and obtain <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $({r}_{0}/\\mathrm{kpc}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>kpc</mml:mi>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn92.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\sigma ,\\beta ,\\alpha )\\,=({0.75}_{-0.16}^{+0.53}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&sgr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:mspace ${0.42}_{-0.15}^{+0.17},-{1.59}_{-0.18}^{+0.19})$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9, as presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft2\">2</xref>. These <italic>&agr;</italic> values are even shallower than those from the full modeling, with the uncertainties being reduced to be comparable to those of previous studies.</p>\n<p>The middle and bottom panels of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff10\">10</xref> are the same as the top panel but for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9, respectively. In contrast to the case for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&minus;7, all the <italic>&agr;</italic>&ndash;<italic>&beta;</italic> combinations from previous observations and <sc>L-Galaxies</sc> are within the 95&percnt; confidence contour of our results. Besides the parameter sets of (<italic>&agr;</italic>, <italic>&beta;</italic>), (<italic>&agr;</italic>, <italic>M</italic>&ast;), (<italic>r</italic><sub>0</sub>, <italic>&beta;</italic>), and (<italic>&sgr;</italic>, <italic>&beta;</italic>) that show correlations at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, <italic>r</italic><sub>0</sub> and <italic>&sgr;</italic> also correlate strongly at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8&ndash;9. This correlation is to reproduce the smaller galaxies and may indicate that we still do not trace the peak of the size distributions at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;8.</p>\n<p>We find that the parameters of the size&ndash;luminosity relations and luminosity functions at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8&ndash;9 are still not well constrained. Thus, there are significant uncertainties in the luminosity function the faint-end slope of the luminosity function <italic>&agr;</italic> and hence in discussions of reionization based on the UV luminosity density.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs5-3\">\n<label>5.3.</label>\n<title>The Modeling of the Size&ndash;Luminosity Relation</title>\n<p>We construct a model to predict the normalization and slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 in the following process, which is referred to as the RL model. (1) We calculate the average stellar mass of galaxies as a function of luminosity using the stellar mass&ndash;luminosity relation by Gonz&aacute;lez et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib43\">2011</xref>). (2) Combining step (1) with the stellar mass&ndash;halo mass relation by Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>), we evaluate the average halo mass of galaxies as a function of luminosity.<xref ref-type=\"fn\" rid=\"apjaaa6cffn3\"><sup>9</sup></xref>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cffn3\">\n<label><sup>9</sup></label>\n<p>There may be a logical inconsistency that we model the steep size&ndash;luminosity relation using the results in Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>), where a luminosity function derived assuming a shallower size&ndash;luminosity relation is used. However, we consider this effect to be of secondary importance.</p>\n</fn> Note that an extrapolated relation covering a wider mass range than that presented in their paper is utilized (P. Behroozi 2016, private communication). (3) We calculate the virial radius of halos by<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn21\">\n<label>21</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{r}_{\\mathrm{vir}}={\\left[\\displaystyle (4) From the halo radius, we calculate the galaxy size based on the equation in Mo et al. the angular momentum and mass, respectively, in the galaxy against those in the halo. In contrast to the original equation in Mo et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib77\">1998</xref>), we allow <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> to vary as a function of the halo mass, whose dependence was suggested in several observational studies (e.g., Okamura et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib84\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2018</xref>; Somerville et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib104\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>) and simulations of galaxy formation (e.g., Sales et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib100\">2010</xref>). The factor <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${({j}_{{\\rm{d}}}/{m}_{{\\rm{d}}})}_{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}=-21}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>m</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>21</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn100.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> and <italic>M</italic><sub>vir,0</sub> represent the <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> and the halo mass of galaxies with <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21, respectively. The index <italic>&gamma;</italic> is the exponent of the mass dependence of <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>. The factor <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>j</italic></sub> equates to the original constant <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> when <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0. The factor <italic>f</italic><sub>c</sub>(<italic>c</italic>), depending only on the concentration parameter of the halo <italic>c</italic>, is to correct for the effect caused by the change in the density profile from the isothermal sphere to the NFW profile. The other factor <italic>f</italic><sub>R</sub>(<italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>, <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>, <italic>&lambda;</italic>, <italic>c</italic>) is to correct for effects caused by the change in the density profile and the gravitational effect by the disk. We need the factor of 1.678 to convert the scale length of the exponential profile to the half-light radius <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>. Thus, we obtain the model of the size&ndash;luminosity relation.</p>\n<p>Except for <italic>&gamma;</italic>, there are four parameters that are needed to calculate the size; while <italic>&lambda;</italic> and <italic>c</italic> are reliably determined in simulations (e.g., Bullock et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib20\">2001</xref>; Vitvitska et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib108\">2002</xref>; Davis &amp; Natarajan <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib30\">2009</xref>; Prada et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib92\">2012</xref>), the parameters <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub> and <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>, depending on baryonic physics, are difficult to predict. In the calculation of the size, we assume <italic>&lambda;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.04 that is independent of redshift, which is consistent with the recent result in Zjupa &amp; Springel (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib114\">2017</xref>). For the concentration parameter <italic>c</italic>, we utilize the fitting function for the <italic>c</italic>&ndash;<italic>M</italic><sub>vir</sub> relation for Planck cosmology in Correa et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib27\">2015</xref>). We assume the typical values of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${({j}_{{\\rm{d}}}/{m}_{{\\rm{d}}})}_{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}=-21}=1.0$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>m</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>21</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.0</mml:mn>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn101.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> (e.g., Fall &amp; Efstathiou <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib37\">1980</xref>; Mo et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib77\">1998</xref>; Romanowsky &amp; Fall <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib99\">2012</xref>; Fall &amp; Romanowsky <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib38\">2013</xref>) and <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.05 (e.g., Sales et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib100\">2010</xref>). These values of <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub> and <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> are shown to be consistent with observations in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-5\">5.5</xref>.</p>\n<p>The calculated size&ndash;luminosity relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 is presented in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff11\">11</xref> as the RL model. We find that the RL model predicts a shallow slope of <italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.3 when <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0. While this shallow slope is consistent with observed slopes at lower redshifts of <italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;0.25 (e.g., de Jong &amp; Lacey <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib31\">2000</xref>; Huang et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>; Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>; see also Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff14\">14</xref>), it is inconsistent with our steep slope at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. However, when we change <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>j</italic></sub> as a function of halo mass with <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.15, the model predicts a steeper slope that is consistent with the observed value at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. This may suggests that <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>, that is, the fraction of the specific angular momentum in the galaxy, is smaller in fainter galaxies at higher redshifts. In the beginning stage of galaxy formation, stars are formed preferentially from gas with lower angular momenta. The halo mass dependence of <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>j</italic></sub> obtained here may suggest that the faint galaxies are indeed in such a stage.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff11\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 11.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc11\">\n<p>Model predictions of the size&ndash;luminosity relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, overplotted with the fitting result to the observation. The black solid and dashed lines show the predictions by the RL model with <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.15 and 0, respectively. The gray dash-dotted, dashed, and solid lines represent the predictions by the Wyithe &amp; Loeb (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib110\">2011</xref>) model with <italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.20, 0.25, and 0.33, respectively, normalized to agree with those by the RL model at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff11_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff11.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff11_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff11_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff11_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff11_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>Stellar feedback may be another explanation because it redistributes the angular momentum between the galaxy and the halo, thus changing <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>j</italic></sub>. Genel et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib42\">2015</xref>) used the Illustris cosmological simulation to find that stellar feedback increases the specific angular momentum of galaxies, although the halo mass dependence is equivalent to <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;0, opposite to what we find here (see also Sales et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib100\">2010</xref> for a contradictory result).</p>\n<p>Another possibility is that in low-mass halos, only those with relatively small spin parameters can form disks, thus making the slope steeper even with <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0. If this is the case, the shape and variance of the log-normal size distribution at faint magnitudes can be different from those at bright magnitudes.</p>\n<p>We also compare the obtained intrinsic slope with analytical predictions by Wyithe &amp; Loeb (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib110\">2011</xref>), which are shown in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff11\">11</xref> with gray lines. They construct a simple analytical model that describes the relation between the size and luminosity (see also Liu et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib69\">2017</xref>). The predicted relation depends on the feedback that dominates in galaxies. They test three kinds of feedback: energy conserving, momentum conserving, and no feedback. The predicted slopes are <italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.20, 0.25, and 0.33, respectively, all of which are shallower than the observed value at &gt;1<italic>&sgr;</italic> levels. We note that they assume a constant <italic>f</italic><sub><italic>j</italic></sub>, which corresponds to <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.</p>\n<p>Very recently, Ma et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib72\">2017</xref>) suggested that UV light does not necessarily trace the main part of galaxies using high-resolution cosmological zoom-in simulations from the FIRE project. This observational bias might affect our discussion presented here and might lead to a smaller <italic>&gamma;</italic> (see also Huang et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib53\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>; Somerville et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib104\">2017</xref>).</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs5-4\">\n<label>5.4.</label>\n<title>The Size&ndash;Luminosity Relations for Derivations of Luminosity Functions</title>\n<p>In this subsection, we examine the effects of the size&ndash;luminosity relation on the estimation of the detected fraction of galaxies, and thus of the luminosity function.</p>\n<p>The top panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff12\">12</xref> shows the detected fraction against UV magnitude for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 calculated for all of the HFF cluster and parallel fields using the best-fit size&ndash;luminosity relation. As shown in this figure, the detected fraction at the faintest magnitudes <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;&minus;15 to &minus;14 is extremely low. This implies that the luminosity function is calculated from only a small part of galaxies in the field of view with a large (&sim;10<sup>3</sup>) incompleteness correction.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff12\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 12.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc12\">\n<p>Top: detected fraction against UV absolute magnitude in each field at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 calculated using the completeness map of the field and the best-fit size&ndash;luminosity relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. The solid and dashed lines correspond to the cluster and parallel fields, respectively. Middle: variation in the detected fractions at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 in the Abell 2744 cluster field calculated with size&ndash;luminosity relations given in previous studies. The uncertainty estimated in this work is also plotted by the red shaded region. Bottom: size&ndash;luminosity relations in the previous studies utilized to calculate the detected fractions in the middle panel, overplotted with the galaxy distributions from this work (red points) and Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>; green points).</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff12_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff12.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff12_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff12_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff12_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff12_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>We calculate the detected fractions, as an example, in the Abell 2744 cluster field assuming the six size&ndash;luminosity relations utilized in the previous studies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 (Atek et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib2\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015a</xref>; Ishigaki et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib55\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>; Laporte et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>; Bouwens et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib13\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017b</xref>; Livermore et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib70\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>). These fractions, together with that calculated assuming our size&ndash;luminosity relation considering its uncertainty, are shown in the middle panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff12\">12</xref>. The assumed size&ndash;luminosity relations are presented in the bottom panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff12\">12</xref>. Whereas the relations in Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib55\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>), have delta-function-like size distributions, those in Atek et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib4\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015b</xref>), Laporte et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2016</xref>), Livermore (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib70\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>), and Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib13\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017b</xref>) have variances of <italic>&sgr;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.9, 0.9, 1.0, and 0.69, respectively. As shown in the bottom panel, all of the size&ndash;luminosity relations in the previous studies are considerably flatter than ours, which results in underestimation of the detected fraction and a steeper faint-end slope of the luminosity function. Furthermore, there is a considerable difference between the relations, which introduces a significant uncertainty in the detected fraction and, consequently, in the luminosity function. In contrast, the uncertainty in the detected fraction calculated by our size&ndash;luminosity relation is smaller than the scatter of the detected fractions by the relations in the previous studies. This means that we reduce the uncertainty in the luminosity function that originates from the size&ndash;luminosity relation (the middle panel of Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff12\">12</xref>).</p>\n<p>Our size&ndash;luminosity relations are more accurate than those in previous studies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9 for three reasons: they are not extrapolations from low-redshift results but are determined directly from large samples with accurate size measurements, they are corrected for detection incompleteness, and proper statistics are utilized.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs5-5\">\n<label>5.5.</label>\n<title>Redshift Evolution of Size</title>\n<p>Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff13\">13</xref> shows the redshift evolution of the size&ndash;luminosity relation. While Oesch et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>), Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib44\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2012</xref>), Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>), Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>), Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>), and Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) showed the relations of LBGs, Roche et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib97\">1996</xref>), de Jong &amp; Lacey (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib31\">2000</xref>), and Jiang et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib59\">2013</xref>) showed those of irregular galaxies, local spiral galaxies, and a combined sample of Ly<italic>&agr;</italic> emitters (LAEs) and LBGs, respectively. The slopes at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9 are slightly steeper than those at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;5 and those derived from bright samples at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6. This may suggest that physical processes that affect the slopes, such as the formation stage, feedback, and transfers and redistributions of angular momentum, differ at around <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6, especially for faint galaxies.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff13\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 13.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc13\">\n<p>Compilation of size&ndash;luminosity relations of LBGs from <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4 to <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9&ndash;10 Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>; Grazian et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib44\">2012</xref>; (Huang et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>, Jiang et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib59\">2013</xref> [LAEs&plus;LBGs], Holwerda et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>; Kawamata et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>; Shibuya et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>) and spiral galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0 (de Jong &amp; Lacey <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib31\">2000</xref>, Shen et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib102\">2003</xref>), with our results plotted by thick solid lines. Redshift is coded by color: purple, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0; violet, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4; blue, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;5; green, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6 (<italic>z</italic> &sim; 6&ndash;7 for our result); yellow, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7; orange, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8; and red, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;9&ndash;10 (<italic>z</italic> &sim; 9 for our result). Different symbols represent the average absolute magnitudes and sizes of different samples: inverse triangles, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;6 samples by Oesch et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>); triangles, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 sample by Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib44\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2012</xref>); and circles, <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;8 samples by Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>). The purple dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the relations of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;0 disk galaxies obtained by the measurements in the <italic>i</italic> band by de Jong &amp; Lacey (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib31\">2000</xref>) and <italic>r</italic> band by Shen et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib102\">2003</xref>), respectively. The violet, blue, and green dashed lines represent the fitting results to the sample of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4 and 5 LBGs by Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) and <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;5.7&ndash;6.5 Ly<italic>&agr;</italic> emitters and LBGs by Jiang et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib59\">2013</xref>), respectively.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff13_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff13.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff13_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff13_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff13_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff13_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff14\">14</xref> shows the redshift evolution of <italic>&beta;</italic> based on LBG samples by two-dimensional profile size measurements. While our fiducial values, where all uncertainties are considered, are plotted with red open circles and thin error bars, values where the parameters of the luminosity functions are fixed to the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 best-fit values are plotted with red filled circles and bold error bars and presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft2\">2</xref>. For comparison, we also plot results from samples of non-LBGs and samples based on other size measurement methods. This figure shows that the slopes of our faint LBGs at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6 are steeper than those of bright or lower-redshift galaxies, which are almost constant at <italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.2&ndash;0.3.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff14\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 14.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc14\">\n<p>Redshift evolution of the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation. The red circles show our measurements, while black symbols show those of LBGs obtained by previous studies with two-dimensional profile fitting. The gray symbols represent results for non-LBG samples or those not based on two-dimensional profile fitting. The error bars correspond to the 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> standard errors. The bold error bars of our samples show the 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> standard errors where the parameters of the luminosity functions are fixed to the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 best-fit values.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff14_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff14.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff14_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff14_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff14_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff14_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>The redshift evolution of sizes at &minus;21&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;19.7 (<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $(0.3-1){L}_{z=3}^{* }$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.3</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>z</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>3</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&ast;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn102.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>) is presented in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff15\">15</xref>, where <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${L}_{z=3}^{* }$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>z</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>3</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&ast;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn103.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> is the characteristic UV luminosity of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;3 LBGs obtained in Steidel et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib106\">1999</xref>). Similar to Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff14\">14</xref>, we plot our fiducial values and values where the parameters of the luminosity functions are fixed. Our samples give consistent results with previous measurements. We fit <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&prop;&nbsp;(1 &plus; <italic>z</italic>)<sup>&minus;<italic>m</italic></sup> to data that are based on two-dimensional size measurements at 4&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;<italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;9.5 (except for those by Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>, because they seem to be considerably smaller than the others). For our data, we use the ones where the parameters of the luminosity functions are fixed for consistency with the previous studies. We obtain <italic>m</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1.28&nbsp;&PlusMinus;&nbsp;0.11, which is consistent within the errors with previous work (Bouwens et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib10\">2004</xref>; Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>; Ono et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib86\">2013</xref>; Holwerda et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>; Kawamata et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>; Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>). The index is predicted by analytical models to be <italic>m</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1.0 for halos with a fixed mass and <italic>m</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1.5 for halos with a fixed circular velocity (e.g., Ferguson et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib39\">2004</xref>). We find that we trace halos in the middle of the two states, as reported in previous work.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff15\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 15.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc15\">\n<p>Redshift evolution of the average size of bright galaxies at &minus;21&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;19.7. The red circles show our measurements, while the black symbols show those of LBGs obtained by previous studies. The gray dashed line represents the best-fit function of <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&prop;&nbsp;(1 &plus; <italic>z</italic>)<sup>&minus;<italic>m</italic></sup> with <italic>m</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1.28. The error bars correspond to the 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> standard errors. The bold error bars of our samples show the 1<italic>&sgr;</italic> standard errors where the parameters of the luminosity functions are fixed to the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 best-fit values.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff15_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff15.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff15_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff15_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff15_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff15_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>We note that the difference in the luminosity range makes the comparison between the samples difficult. The average luminosities of individual samples plotted in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff13\">13</xref> have some variance, as shown in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft3\">3</xref>. For instance, at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;7, a difference of 0.5 mag in luminosity corresponds to a difference in stellar mass of &Delta;<italic>M</italic>&ast;/<italic>M</italic>&ast;&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;54&percnt;, assuming the mass&ndash;luminosity relation in Gonz&aacute;lez et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib43\">2011</xref>). Based on the stellar mass&ndash;halo mass relation by Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>), the difference in stellar mass at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21 is equivalent to those in halo mass and halo radius of &Delta; <italic>M</italic><sub>vir</sub>/<italic>M</italic><sub>vir</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;52&percnt; and &Delta;<italic>r</italic><sub>vir</sub>/<italic>r</italic><sub>vir</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;21&percnt;, respectively. Since the galaxy size is fundamentally proportional to the halo size, the expected galaxy size would differ &Delta;<italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>/<italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;21&percnt;. This means that the difference between samples in the luminosity range introduces a systematic uncertainty into the discussion of the evolution of the average size, which is conventional in previous studies.</p>\n<table-wrap id=\"apjaaa6cft3\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Table 3</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cftc3\">\n<p>Luminosities where the Average Sizes in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff15\">15</xref> Are Calculated</p>\n</caption>\n<table>\n<colgroup>\n<col align=\"left\"/>\n<col align=\"char\" char=\".\"/>\n</colgroup>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th align=\"left\">References</th>\n<th align=\"center\">\n<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\overline{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mover accent=\"true\">\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&macr;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mover>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn104.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>\n</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">This work</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;21</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Bouwens et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib86\">2013</xref>) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;20.2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Ono et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;20.2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;20.30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Holwerda et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib51\">2015</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;20.87</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;21</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"left\">Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>)</td>\n<td align=\"char\" char=\".\">&minus;20.35</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft3_tb.gif\"/>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft3_lr.gif\">\n<caption>\n<p>Typeset image</p>\n</caption>\n</graphic>\n</table-wrap>\n<p>In order to resolve the above problem and further investigate the size evolution of galaxies, we calculate the evolution of the galaxy size&ndash;halo size ratio following <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> (see also Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>; Okamura et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib84\">2018</xref>). We calculate size ratios with a similar method to that for the model construction described in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-3\">5.3</xref>. In order to estimate the average halo size of each sample from its average luminosity, we make use of the stellar mass&ndash;luminosity relation in Reddy &amp; Steidel (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib94\">2009</xref>) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;2.5 and that in Gonz&aacute;lez et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib43\">2011</xref>) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;9.5, the stellar mass&ndash;halo mass relation (Behroozi et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>), and Equation (<xref ref-type=\"disp-formula\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfeqn21\">21</xref>). Then, we obtain the size ratio by dividing the galaxy size by the halo size. The stellar mass&ndash;luminosity relation in Gonz&aacute;lez et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib43\">2011</xref>) is originally obtained at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;7, but we also apply the relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8&ndash;9.5. In the above process, the variance in luminosity between the samples is corrected for because fainter samples are assigned smaller halo sizes. The result is shown in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff16\">16</xref>. We confirm that the size ratio is roughly constant over the wide redshift range of 2.5&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;7.0, and the average ratio is 2.80&percnt;&nbsp;&PlusMinus;&nbsp;0.10&percnt; over this redshift range. This value is in good agreement with those obtained in previous studies (Kawamata et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>; Shibuya et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>; Huang et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib53\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>; Okamura et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib84\">2018</xref>; Somerville et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib104\">2017</xref>).</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff16\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 16.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc16\">\n<p>Redshift evolution of the galaxy size&ndash;halo size ratio. Our samples are shown with red circles, and those from previous studies are in black. The errors in disk sizes only (plotted in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff15\">15</xref>) are considered. The gray dashed line shows the average size ratio. The red, green, and blue shaded bands represent the ratio predicted by the model described in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-5\">5.5</xref> with <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${({j}_{{\\rm{d}}}/{m}_{{\\rm{d}}})}_{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}=-21}=1.5$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>m</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>21</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.5</mml:mn>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn105.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, 1.0, and 0.5, respectively, where the width of each band indicates a weak dependence of the ratio on <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> and the upper and lower edges of each band correspond to <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.05 and 0.1, respectively.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff16_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff16.eps\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff16_lr\" content-type=\"low\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff16_lr.jpg\"/>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff16_hr\" content-type=\"high\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cff16_hr.jpg\"/>\n</fig>\n<p>It appears from Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff15\">15</xref> that the average size continues to decrease with redshift at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;7. This trend, if true, predicts that the size ratio starts to decrease at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;7 because the denominator (halo mass, and hence halo size, of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;&minus;21 galaxies) increases with redshift at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;7 according to the stellar mass&ndash;halo mass relation by Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>). This prediction is consistent with our size ratio measurements at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9 within the errors. This decreasing trend in the size ratio was not observed in our previous work, <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>, because <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> linearly extrapolated the stellar mass&ndash;halo mass relation at <italic>M</italic><sub>h</sub>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;10<sup>11</sup> <italic>M</italic><sub>&CircleDot;</sub>, while in reality, it has a knee at <italic>M</italic><sub>h</sub>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;10<sup>11.3</sup> <italic>M</italic><sub>&CircleDot;</sub>, thus resulting in underestimation of the halo masses.</p>\n<p>We compare the observed size ratios with those predicted by the model constructed in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-3\">5.3</xref> with <italic>&gamma;</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0,<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn25\">\n<label>25</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}\\displaystyle {f}_{{\\rm{c}}}^{-1/2}{f}_{{\\rm{R}}}.\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mstyle xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfeqn25.gif\"/>\n</disp-formula>Since <italic>f</italic><sub>R</sub> strongly depends on <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> and weakly on <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>, the only uncertain parameter to calculate the size ratio is <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${({j}_{{\\rm{d}}}/{m}_{{\\rm{d}}})}_{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}=-21}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo
