Following <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>, we change <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${({j}_{{\\rm{d}}}/{m}_{{\\rm{d}}})}_{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}=-21}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>m</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>21</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn107.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> with the updated size measurements and simulation results of <italic>&lambda;</italic> and <italic>c</italic>. Model-predicted size ratios are presented in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff16\">16</xref>. Since they weakly depend on <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>, we show with bands the uncertainty due to <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> within the range of 0.05&ndash;0.1. If we assume the typical value of 0.05 for <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> (e.g., Sales et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib100\">2010</xref>), we confirm that the observed size ratios are in good accordance with the model ratios premised on <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21. This is why we have assumed <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA ${({j}_{{\\rm{d}}}/{m}_{{\\rm{d}}})}_{{M}_{\\mathrm{UV}}=-21}=1.0$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mml:mo>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>j</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"true\">&sol;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>m</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>M</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>UV</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>21</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.0</mml:mn>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn108.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> and <italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.05 when modeling the size&ndash;luminosity relation in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5-3\">5.3</xref>.</p>\n<p>Using a mass-complete sample at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;1&ndash;7 from the FourStar Galaxy Evolution Survey, Allen et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib1\">2017</xref>) found a slower size evolution of <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&prop;&nbsp;(1 &plus; <italic>z</italic>)<sup>&minus;0.97&PlusMinus;0.02</sup>. Since the size evolution of LBGs is faster, they have concluded that LBGs do not represent the entire galaxy population. Considering their results, it should be noted that this study also might not be tracing the entire galaxy population at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9.</p>\n</sec>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs6\">\n<label>6.</label>\n<title>Conclusion</title>\n<p>We have measured the intrinsic sizes and magnitudes of 334, 61, and 37 faint dropout galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively, from the complete HFF data, properly correcting for the lensing effects by fitting the lensed images with lensing-distorted S&eacute;rsic profiles. These represent the largest samples, especially at faint magnitudes of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;18 to &minus;12, where luminosity function measurements have been made possible only recently. Systematic and random errors in sizes and magnitudes have been carefully estimated using Monte Carlo simulations.</p>\n<p>Although the HFF observations reach the faintest galaxies with the help of cluster lensing, our samples still suffer from the incompleteness that faint but large galaxies are not detected in observations. Since the degree of incompleteness strongly depends on the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation, we have conducted simultaneous maximum-likelihood estimation of the luminosity function and size&ndash;luminosity relation from the observed distribution of galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane and examined correlations between the luminosity function and size&ndash;luminosity relation.</p>\n<p>We have also updated our mass models for Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403,&nbsp;as well as newly constructed models for Abell S1063 and Abell 370, all of which are publicly available through the STScI website. The following are the main results of this paper.<list id=\"apjaaa6cfl1\" list-type=\"roman-lower\">\n<list-item id=\"apjaaa6cfl1.1\">\n<label>i.</label>\n<p>We have found that the slope of the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation of faint galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 is considerably steeper (<italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.46) than those (<italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.22&ndash;0.25) at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;5 and those (<italic>&beta;</italic>&nbsp;&simeq;&nbsp;0.25) assumed in previous studies of the luminosity function at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7. As a result of the steep size&ndash;luminosity relation, a shallow faint-end slope of the luminosity function of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\alpha =-{1.86}_{-0.18}^{+0.17}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.86</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.18</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.17</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn109.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> has been derived. The values of <italic>&beta;</italic> and <italic>&agr;</italic> at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9 are consistent with those at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 but have large errors due to small sample sizes. Thus, at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9, the UV luminosity density is still highly uncertain, which has to be taken into account in the discussion of cosmic reionization.</p>\n</list-item>\n<list-item id=\"apjaaa6cfl1.2\">\n<label>ii.</label>\n<p>We have quantified the correlation between the parameters of the size&ndash;luminosity relation and luminosity function. Among the parameter pairs, we have found strong correlations between the faint-end slope of the luminosity function and the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation, (<italic>&agr;</italic>, <italic>&beta;</italic>), and between the faint-end slope and the characteristic magnitude of the luminosity function, (<italic>&agr;</italic>, <italic>M</italic>&ast;). Although the values of <italic>&agr;</italic> in several previous studies are consistent with our measurements, some of the previous results have been found to be located outside our confidence region in the <italic>&agr;</italic>&ndash;<italic>&beta;</italic> plane.</p>\n</list-item>\n<list-item id=\"apjaaa6cfl1.3\">\n<label>iii.</label>\n<p>We have constructed an analytical model to reproduce the steep slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 utilizing the result of the abundance matching in Behroozi et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib6\">2013</xref>). We have found that the steepness is not reproduced when <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub> is constant within the magnitude range studied here. One possible explanation for the steepness is that a smaller fraction of the specific angular momentum is transferred to the disk from its halo at fainter magnitudes. Another possible explanation is that low-mass halos can host galaxies only when they have relatively small halo spin parameters.</p>\n</list-item>\n<list-item id=\"apjaaa6cfl1.4\">\n<label>iv.</label>\n<p>The average size at (<inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $0.3-1){L}_{z=3}^{* }$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mn>0.3</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>z</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>3</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&ast;</mml:mo>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn110.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> gradually decreases with redshift with (1 &plus; <italic>z</italic>)<sup>&minus;<italic>m</italic></sup>, where <italic>m</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;1.28&nbsp;&PlusMinus;&nbsp;0.11 over a redshift range of 4&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;9.5. However, we have pointed out that this conventional discussion of the size evolution suffers from systematic biases due to a variance in average luminosity between the samples. In order to overcome this issue, we have calculated the disk-to-halo size ratio to find <italic>j</italic><sub>d</sub>/<italic>m</italic><sub>d</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;1 at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;&minus;21.</p>\n</list-item>\n</list>\n</p>\n</sec> </body>\n<back>\n<ack>\n<p>We would like to thank the anonymous referee for valuable comments that improved our paper. We would like to thank Michael Fall, Rychard Bouwens, Rebecca Bowler, Henry Ferguson, Kentaro Nagamine, Pascal Oesch, Yoshiaki Ono, Takatoshi Shibuya, Tsutomu Takeuchi, Haruka Kusakabe, Taku Okamura, and Kazushi Irikura for their helpful comments. We are grateful to Peter Behroozi, Chuanwu Liu, and Takatoshi Shibuya for kindly providing us with their results. This work was supported in part by a Grant-in-Aid for JSPS Research Fellow (JP16J01302, JP16J03727) and by a KAKENHI (JP16K05286) Grant-in-Aid for Scientific Research (C) through the Japan Society for the Promotion of Science (JSPS). This work was supported in part by the World Premier International Research Center Initiative (WPI Initiative), MEXT, Japan, and JSPS KAKENHI Grant Number JP26800093 and JP15H05892. This work used the 2015 public version of the Munich model of galaxy formation and evolution, L-GALAXIES. The source code and a full description of the model are available at&nbsp;<ext-link ext-link-type=\"uri\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"http://galformod.mpa-garching.mpg.de/public/LGalaxies/\">http://galformod.mpa-garching.mpg.de/public/LGalaxies/</ext-link>. The Millennium and Millennium-II simulation databases used in this paper and the web application providing online access to them were constructed as part of the activities of the German Astrophysical Virtual Observatory (GAVO).</p>\n</ack>\n<app-group id=\"apjaaa6cfapp\">\n<app id=\"apjaaa6cfapp1\">\n<label>Appendix A</label>\n<title>Mass Models</title>\n<p>Among the six HFF clusters, we use our version 3 mass models constructed in Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">2016</xref>) for MACS J0717.5&plus;3745 and MACS J1149.6&plus;2223; update the version 3 models for Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403, which are now referred to as version 4 models; and newly construct mass models for the last two clusters, Abell S1063 and Abell 370, also referred to as version 4. In this section, we describe the two updated and the two newly constructed models, whose modeling strategy is the same as that established in Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">2016</xref>). The lensing calculation is conducted using <monospace>glafic</monospace> (Oguri <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib83\">2010</xref>), which adopts a parametric modeling method. A summary of the mass modeling is presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft4\">4</xref>, including the numbers of multiple images and the reduced <italic>&chi;</italic><sup>2</sup>. The best-fit parameters of the mass components are shown in Tables <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft5\">5</xref>&ndash;<xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft8\">8</xref>. Tables <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft9\">9</xref>&ndash;<xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft12\">12</xref> show the position and redshift constraints of the multiple images for each cluster, which are utilized in the model constructions. The positions of the multiple images and the critical curves of the best-fit models are shown in Figure <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff17\">17</xref>. The root mean squares of the distances between positions of observed and model-predicted multiple images on the image plane are presented in Table <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft4\">4</xref>. The relatively small root mean squares for our models indicate that they well reproduce the observations despite strict constraints due to large numbers of multiple images and spectroscopic redshifts.</p>\n<fig id=\"apjaaa6cff17\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Figure 17.</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cffc17\">\n<p>Multiple image systems used for mass modeling for Abell 2744 (upper left), MACS J0416.1&minus;2403 (upper right), Abell S1063 (middle left), and Abell 370 (middle right). The bottom panel shows zoomed-in images of System 2 in the Abell 370 field. Underlying color-composite images are created from the <italic>HST B</italic><sub>435</sub>&plus;<italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub>-, <italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub>&plus;<italic>Y</italic><sub>105</sub>-, and <italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>&plus;<italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>&plus;<italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub>-band images. Small yellow squares show the positions of multiple images (see Tables <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft9\">9</xref>&ndash;<xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft12\">12</xref> for details). Critical curves for a source redshift of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;8 are shown with white solid lines.</p>\n</caption>\n<graphic id=\"apjaaa6cff17_eps\" content-type=\"print\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft12_lr.gif\">\n<caption>\n<p>1</p>\n</caption>\n</graphic>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft12a_tb.gif\"/>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft12a_lr.gif\">\n<caption>\n<p>2</p>\n</caption>\n</graphic>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft12b_tb.gif\"/>\n<graphic xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cft12b_lr.gif\">\n<caption>\n<p>3</p>\n</caption>\n</graphic>\n<table-wrap-foot>\n<p><bold>Note.</bold></p>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cft12fnb\">\n<label><sup>a</sup></label>\n<p>JR10&mdash;Richard et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib96\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2010</xref>), JR14&mdash;Richard et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib95\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), JD&mdash;Diego et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib34\">2018</xref>), DL&mdash;Lagattuta et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib66\">2017</xref>).</p>\n</fn>\n</table-wrap-foot>\n</table-wrap>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfapp1-1\">\n<label>A.1.</label>\n<title>Updated Model for Abell 2744</title>\n<p>After the publication of Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">2016</xref>), a new mass model was published by Mahler et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib73\">2018</xref>) that exploits new multiple images and spectroscopic redshifts of multiple images revealed by the MUSE observation. Considering the results of the MUSE observation, we update our model by incorporating and removing 25 and six positions of multiple images, respectively. Specifically, we incorporate multiple image systems 39, 40, 42, 47, 50, 61, 63, and 147 and remove IDs 2.3, 5.1, 5.4, and 8.3 and system 62. The positions of IDs 33.3 and 34.3 are corrected. In addition, we incorporate 20 MUSE spectroscopic redshifts that are considered to be reliable based on their qualities and consistency with our mass model. The spectroscopic redshift of system 1 is updated, and 19 redshifts are newly determined for systems 2, 5, 8, 10, 22, 24, 26, 30, 31, 33, 34, 39, 40, 41, 42, 47, 61, 63, and 147. We add a mass component representing a multipole perturbation in order to better fit the observations. While the image plane rms increases by 0&farcs;05, the reduced <italic>&chi;</italic><sup>2</sup> slightly decreases by 0.01 compared to our version 3 model.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfapp1-2\">\n<label>A.2.</label>\n<title>Updated Model for MACS J0416.1&minus;2403</title>\n<p>After the publication of Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">2016</xref>), a new mass model was published by Caminha et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib22\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>) that exploits new multiple images and spectroscopic redshifts of multiple images revealed by the MUSE observation. Considering the results of the MUSE observation, we update our model by incorporating 22 positions of multiple images. Specifically, we incorporate systems 26, 58, 67, 92, 94, 95, 96, and 97, among which system 97 is found for the first time in this work. The position of ID 91.3 is corrected. In addition, we incorporate 18 MUSE spectroscopic redshifts that are considered to be reliable based on their qualities and consistency with our mass model. The spectroscopic redshifts incorporated are for systems 26, 33, 25, 38, 44, 47, 48, 49, 51, 55, 58, 67, 86, 91, 92, 94, 95, and 96. The image plane rms increases by 0&farcs;06, and the reduced <italic>&chi;</italic><sup>2</sup> increases by 0.30 compared to our version 3 model.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfapp1-3\">\n<label>A.3.</label>\n<title>Newly Constructed Model for Abell S1063</title>\n<p>In order to construct a mass model for Abell S1063, we use multiple images identified in Balestra et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib5\">2013</xref>), Monna et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib78\">2014</xref>), Richard et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib95\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), Johnson et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib60\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), Karman et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib62\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>) Caminha et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib21\">2016a</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib23\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2016b</xref>), Diego et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib33\">2016</xref>), and Karman et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib61\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>). Spectroscopic redshifts of multiple images were obtained in Balestra et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib5\">2013</xref>), Richard et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib95\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), Johnson et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib60\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), Karman et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib62\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>), Caminha et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib21\">2016a</xref>), Karman et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib61\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>), and the GLASS program (Schmidt et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib101\">2014a</xref>; Treu et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib107\">2015</xref>). In addition, we find three new counterimages and 13 new systems, which sums up to 35 new multiple images. As a result, we use 40 systems from the literature and 13 new systems; the total number of multiple images is 141. The positional uncertainty in the multiple images is assumed to be <italic>&sgr;</italic><sub><italic>x</italic></sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0&farcs;4 for all of them.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfapp1-4\">\n<label>A.4.</label>\n<title>Newly Constructed Model for Abell 370</title>\n<p>In order to construct a mass model for Abell 370, we use multiple images identified in Richard et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib96\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2010</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib95\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), Johnson et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib60\">2014</xref>), Diego et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib34\">2018</xref>), and Lagattuta et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib66\">2017</xref>). Spectroscopic redshifts of multiple images were obtained in Richard et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib96\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2010</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib95\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>), Lagattuta et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib66\">2017</xref>), and the GLASS program (Schmidt et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib101\">2014a</xref>; Treu et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib107\">2015</xref>). We correct the positions of four multiple images of IDs 3.3, 8.3, 13.3, and 26.3. In addition, we find two new counterimages and 16 new systems, which sums up to 40 new multiple images. As a result, we use 33 systems from the literature and 16 new systems; the total number of multiple images is 135. The positional uncertainty in the multiple images is assumed to be <italic>&sgr;</italic><sub><italic>x</italic></sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0&farcs;4 for all of them.</p>\n</sec>\n</app>\n<app id=\"apjaaa6cfapp2\">\n<label>Appendix B</label>\n<title>Fitting Results</title>\n<p>The obtained morphological properties and magnitudes are presented in Tables <xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft13\">13</xref>&ndash;<xref ref-type=\"table\" rid=\"apjaaa6cft15\">15</xref>. The fitting results for galaxies fainter than &minus;18 mag are graphically shown in Figures <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff18\">18</xref> and <xref ref-type=\"fig\" rid=\"apjaaa6cff19\">19</xref>.</p>\n<table-wrap id=\"apjaaa6cft13\" position=\"float\">\n<label>Table 13</label>\n<caption id=\"apjaaa6cftc13\">\n<p>Fitting Results for Dropouts at ${r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{\\mathrm{maj}}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi id=\"apjaaa6cfaf6\">\n<label>6</label>\n<institution>Institute of Astronomy, University of Cambridge</institution>, Madingley Road, Cambridge, CB3 0HA, <country>UK</country>\n</aff>\n<author-comment content-type=\"short-author-list\">\n<p>Kawamata et al.</p>\n</author-comment>\n</contrib-group>\n<pub-date pub-type=\"ppub\">\n<day>1</day>\n<month>3</month>\n<year>2018</year>\n</pub-date>\n<pub-date pub-type=\"epub\">\n<day>27</day>\n<month>02</month>\n<year>2018</year>\n</pub-date>\n<volume>855</volume>\n<issue>1</issue>\n<elocation-id content-type=\"artnum\">4</elocation-id>\n<history>\n<date date-type=\"received\">\n<day>17</day>\n<month>10</month>\n<year>2017</year>\n</date>\n<date date-type=\"rev-recd\">\n<day>8</day>\n<month>12</month>\n<year>2017</year>\n</date>\n<date date-type=\"accepted\">\n<day>4</day>\n<month>1</month>\n<year>2018</year>\n</date>\n</history>\n<permissions>\n<copyright-statement>&copy; 2018. The American Astronomical Society. All rights reserved.</copyright-statement>\n<copyright-year>2018</copyright-year>\n</permissions>\n<self-uri xlink:href=\"http://stacks.iop.org/apj/855/4\"/>\n<abstract>\n<title>Abstract</title>\n<p>We construct <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9 faint Lyman break galaxy samples (334, 61, and 37 galaxies, respectively) with accurate size measurements with the software <monospace>glafic</monospace> from the complete <italic>Hubble</italic> Frontier Fields (HFF) cluster and parallel fields data. These are the largest samples hitherto and reach down to the faint ends of recently obtained deep luminosity functions. At faint magnitudes, however, these samples are highly incomplete for galaxies with large sizes, implying that derivation of the luminosity function sensitively depends on the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation. We thus conduct simultaneous maximum-likelihood estimation of luminosity function and size&ndash;luminosity relation parameters from the observed distribution of galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane with the help of a completeness map as a function of size and luminosity. At <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, we find that the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation expressed as <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub>&nbsp;&prop;&nbsp;<italic>L</italic><sup><italic>&beta;</italic></sup> has a notably steeper slope of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\beta ={0.46}_{-0.09}^{+0.08}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&beta;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.46</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.09</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.08</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn1.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> than those at lower redshifts, which in turn implies that the luminosity function has a relatively shallow faint-end slope of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $\\alpha =-{1.86}_{-0.18}^{+0.17}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>&agr;</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&equals;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>1.86</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.18</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mo>&plus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.17</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn2.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. This steep <italic>&beta;</italic> can be reproduced by a simple analytical model in which smaller galaxies have lower specific angular momenta. The <italic>&beta;</italic> and <italic>&agr;</italic> values for the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;8 and 9 samples are consistent with those for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 but with larger errors. For all three samples, there is a large, positive covariance between <italic>&beta;</italic> and <italic>&agr;</italic>, implying that the simultaneous determination of these two parameters is important. We also provide new strong lens mass models of Abell S1063 and Abell 370, as well as updated mass models of Abell 2744 and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403.</p>\n</abstract>\n<kwd-group kwd-group-type=\"AAS\">\n<kwd>galaxies: evolution</kwd>\n<kwd>galaxies: high-redshift</kwd>\n<kwd>galaxies: structure</kwd>\n<kwd>gravitational lensing: strong</kwd>\n</kwd-group>\n<counts>\n<page-count count=\"47\"/>\n</counts>\n<custom-meta-group>\n<custom-meta>\n<meta-name>ccc</meta-name>\n<meta-value>0004-637X/18/4&plus;47&dollar;33.00</meta-value>\n</custom-meta>\n<custom-meta>\n<meta-name>crossmark</meta-name>\n<meta-value>yes</meta-value>\n</custom-meta>\n</custom-meta-group>\n</article-meta>\n</front>\n<body>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs1\">\n<label>1.</label>\n<title>Introduction</title>\n<p>Disk sizes of galaxies at very high redshifts are important in two aspects. One is that they provide information on the formation and early evolution of galaxies. The other is that they have a significant effect on the determination of UV luminosity functions because the correction for detection incompleteness sensitively depends on size.</p>\n<p>Concerning the first aspect, the size of galaxies is largely determined by their angular momentum (e.g., Fall &amp; Efstathiou <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib37\">1980</xref>; Mo et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib77\">1998</xref>), as is the case for disk galaxies, and angular momentum is one of the fundamental parameters of galaxies as argued by Fall (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib36\">1983</xref>). Romanowsky &amp; Fall (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib99\">2012</xref>) and Fall &amp; Romanowsky (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib38\">2013</xref>) discussed galaxy formation and evolution using the specific angular momentum&ndash;mass diagram. Indeed, numerous simulations and analytical models of galaxy formation suggest that the size of galaxies changes with a redistribution of the angular momentum in them due to stellar feedback such as galactic winds (e.g., Brooks et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib18\">2011</xref>; Wyithe &amp; Loeb <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib110\">2011</xref>; Brook et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib17\">2012</xref>; Danovich et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib29\">2015</xref>; Genel et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib42\">2015</xref>). Recently, high-resolution cosmological simulations have succeeded in increasing sizes at a fixed luminosity or stellar mass of simulated galaxies to reproduce observed sizes by incorporating stellar feedback such as galactic winds of high mass-loading factors (e.g., Brooks et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib18\">2011</xref>; Genel et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib42\">2015</xref>). The luminosity dependence of the size is also affected by stellar feedback as explained by simple analytical models. For example, Wyithe &amp; Loeb (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib110\">2011</xref>) showed that the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation varies depending on the dominating feedback, such as energy-driven and momentum-driven feedback. Larger sizes indicate more efficient feedback, which suggests that the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation contains information on the dominant feedback process.</p>\n<p>The second aspect concerning UV luminosity functions is also important because luminosity functions are determined by correcting for detection completeness, which depends on the intrinsic size distribution. For a given magnitude, galaxies with larger sizes are less likely to be detected because of their lower surface brightness. Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib45\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2011</xref>), based on the <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 analysis, pointed out that the assumed size distribution critically alters the UV luminosity function, especially the faint-end slope.</p>\n<p>One of the main goals of recent observational projects targeting <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6 galaxies (e.g., Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>; Grogin et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib47\">2011</xref>; Koekemoer et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib65a\">2011</xref>; Ellis et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib35\">2013</xref>; Illingworth et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib55a\">2013</xref>; Ono et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib87\">2018</xref>) is to obtain the faint-end slope of luminosity functions, a key quantity for testing galaxy formation models. In addition, since <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;10 is the epoch of reionization and faint galaxies are thought to be major sources of ionizing photons, the abundance of faint galaxies, i.e., the faint-end slope, is important for understanding the reionization of the universe.</p>\n<p>Recently, in order to derive luminosity functions at fainter magnitudes, deep observations combined with the power of the gravitational lensing by galaxy clusters have been conducted, such as the CLASH program (see Postman et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib91\">2012</xref> for more details) and the <italic>Hubble</italic> Frontier Fields program (HFF; Lotz et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib71\">2017</xref>). Utilizing early-stage data from the HFF, the faint limits of luminosity functions reach as faint as UV magnitudes (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>) of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;15.5, &minus;17, and &minus;17.5 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9, respectively (Atek et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib3\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2014</xref>, <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib4\">2015b</xref>; Ishigaki et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib55\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2015</xref>; McLeod et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib74\">2015</xref>). More recently, very faint galaxies of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;13 at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 have been detected using one-third of the full HFF data (Castellano et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib24\">2016</xref>; Livermore et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib70\">2017</xref>), half of them (Laporte et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>), two-thirds of them (Kawamata et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">2016</xref>, hereafter <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib64\">K16</xref>; Yue et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib111\">2017</xref>), and all of them (Ishigaki et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>). However, the luminosity functions obtained in the previous studies, including those from the HFF, are still highly uncertain, especially at <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;&minus;18 and <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6, because the size&ndash;luminosity relations are not determined well in that magnitude range (see our Figure 12 and Figure 2 of Bouwens et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) owing to an insufficient number of galaxies with size measurements.</p>\n<p>There have been a number of studies that measure sizes of bright (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;18) galaxies (e.g., Bouwens et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib10\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2004</xref>; Ferguson et al. <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib39\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2004</xref>; Curtis-Lake et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib28\">2016</xref>; Laporte et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>; Bowler et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib15\">2017</xref>). At <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4 and 5, Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) carefully measured the size distributions of Lyman break galaxies (LBGs) with &minus;22.5&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;17.5 and found size&ndash;luminosity relations of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.22-0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.22</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn3.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>, where <italic>L</italic> and <italic>r</italic><sub>e</sub> are the luminosity and effective half-light radius, respectively. Oesch et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib80\">2010a</xref>) were among the first to measure the sizes of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 and 8 galaxies with samples of 16 and five galaxies from HUDF09 (Oesch et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib81\">2010b</xref>), reporting that the decreasing trend of sizes with increasing redshifts continues to these redshifts. This trend was confirmed by Ono et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib86\">2013</xref>) by careful measurements using the deeper imaging data from HUDF12 (Ellis et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib35\">2013</xref>; Koekemoer et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib65\">2013</xref>). With a larger sample, Grazian et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib44\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2012</xref>) measured the sizes of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;7 LBGs of moderate magnitude (<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;18.5). They found that the size&ndash;luminosity relation is in the form of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.5}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.5</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn4.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> at this redshift, although their size measurements may suffer from systematic biases due to their measuring method. More recently, Shibuya et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib103\">2015</xref>) measured sizes for large <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&minus;10 LBG samples with moderate magnitudes of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;18. However, since none of the above studies has reliably determined the size&ndash;luminosity relation for <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;18 galaxies at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;6, a size&ndash;luminosity relation of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn5.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula> has been commonly adopted, given the results of Huang et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib54\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2013</xref>) obtained for <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;4&ndash;5. This relation is extrapolated and also applied to fainter magnitudes down to <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;&minus;13, beyond the magnitude range over which it is determined.</p>\n<p>At faint magnitudes of <italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&gsim;&nbsp;&minus;18, Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>; hereafter <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref>) used the first cluster and parallel fields data from the HFF to find that the sizes of observed faint galaxies (&minus;18.7&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub> &lsim; &minus;16.6) are considerably smaller than the sizes inferred from the extrapolated size&ndash;luminosity relation of <inline-formula>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA $L\\propto {r}_{{\\rm{e}}}^{0.25}$?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:mi>L</mml:mi>\n<mml:mo>&prop;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msubsup>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>r</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>0.25</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msubsup>\n</mml:math> -->\n<inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"apjaaa6cfieqn6.gif\"/>\n</inline-formula>. This result was subsequently confirmed by Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>), Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>), and Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib14\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017c</xref>), who measured the sizes of faint galaxies using four, three, and four HFF cluster fields data, respectively. In addition, Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) indirectly indicated the absence of faint galaxies with large sizes using the dependence of the galaxy surface density on the lensing shear. They concluded that the intrinsic sizes of the faintest galaxies are small, and the intrinsic size distribution assumed in the calculation of the luminosity function should be close to the observed one. This makes the faint-end slope of the luminosity function shallower. However, since none of Kawamata et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">2015</xref>), Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>, <xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib14\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017c</xref>), and Laporte et al. (<xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib68\">2016</xref>) considered an incompleteness correction due to galaxies with large sizes, the slope of the size&ndash;luminosity relation may be biased toward a steeper value. In addition, the indirect inference in Bouwens et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib12\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017a</xref>) is subject to large uncertainties, which may result in weak constraints on the size distribution compared to inferences using direct size measurements.</p>\n<p>In this paper, we provide direct size measurements of <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7, 8, and 9 LBGs at &minus;21.6&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>UV</sub>&nbsp;&lsim;&nbsp;&minus;12.3 using all six HFF cluster and parallel fields data. We show that the incompleteness effect is significant at <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;9 for the first time. We derive incompleteness-corrected intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relations simultaneously with luminosity functions, which enables us to explore the correlation between these two functions. We note that we do not discuss the UV luminosity density and hence the contribution of galaxies to cosmic reionization, because the normalization parameter of UV luminosity functions is not determined in this paper.</p>\n<p>The structure of this paper is as follows. In Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs2\">2</xref>, we describe the data and samples, which are identical to those constructed in Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>) but with slight changes. In Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs3\">3</xref>, we measure the sizes of the galaxies. Our method to correct for systematic biases, which is updated from that in <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib63\">K15</xref> in order to deal with the increased number of galaxies, is also described. In Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs4\">4</xref>, for each of the three redshift ranges, we simultaneously estimate the intrinsic size&ndash;luminosity relation and the UV luminosity function from the observed distribution of galaxies on the size&ndash;luminosity plane, taking account of the incompleteness effect. The correlations between the size&ndash;luminosity and luminosity function parameters are also obtained. We discuss our findings in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs5\">5</xref> and give a summary in Section <xref ref-type=\"sec\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfs6\">6</xref>.</p>\n<p>Throughout this paper, we adopt a cosmology with &OHgr;<sub><italic>M</italic></sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.3, &OHgr;<sub>&Lambda;</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;0.7, and <italic>H</italic><sub>0</sub>&nbsp;&equals;&nbsp;70 km s<sup>&minus;1</sup> Mpc<sup>&minus;1</sup>. Magnitudes are given in the AB system (Oke &amp; Gunn <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib85\">1983</xref>). Galaxy sizes are measured in the physical scale.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs2\">\n<label>2.</label>\n<title>Data and Sample Selection</title>\n<p>Here we describe the data, sample selection, and obtained samples. The data and the criteria for the sample selection are the same as those in Ishigaki et al. (<xref rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib56\" ref-type=\"bibr\">2017</xref>), but we remove two galaxies from their samples. Only a brief description is given in this section, and readers are referred to the above paper for further details.</p>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs2-1\">\n<label>2.1.</label>\n<title>HFF Mosaic Data</title>\n<p>We use the reduced image mosaics obtained in the HFF program, which are made publicly available through the STScI website.<xref ref-type=\"fn\" rid=\"apjaaa6cffn1\"><sup>7</sup></xref>\n<fn id=\"apjaaa6cffn1\">\n<label><sup>7</sup></label>\n<p>\n<ext-link ext-link-type=\"uri\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"http://www.stsci.edu/hst/campaigns/frontier-fields/\">http://www.stsci.edu/hst/campaigns/frontier-fields/</ext-link>\n</p>\n</fn> This program targets six cluster fields&mdash;Abell 2744, MACS J0416.1&minus;2403, MACS J0717.5&plus;3745, MACS J1149.6&plus;2223, Abell S1063, and Abell 370&mdash;and their accompanying six parallel fields. Those fields have been observed deeply with the <italic>Hubble Space Telescope</italic> using three bands of the Advanced Camera for Surveys (ACS) and four bands of the IR channel of the Wide Field Camera 3 (WFC3/IR). We utilize the v1.0 standard calibrated (i.e., without &ldquo;self-calibration&rdquo;) mosaics for the three ACS bands F435W (<italic>B</italic><sub>435</sub>), F606W (<italic>V</italic><sub>606</sub>), and F814W (<italic>i</italic><sub>814</sub>). For the four WFC3/IR bands F105W (<italic>Y</italic><sub>105</sub>), F125W (<italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>), F140W (<italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>), and F160W (<italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub>), we use the v1.0 standard calibrated mosaics for the Abell 2744 parallel and MACS J0416.1&minus;2403 cluster fields and v1.0 mosaics corrected for &ldquo;time-variable sky emission&rdquo; for the other 10 fields. The 5<italic>&sgr;</italic> limiting magnitudes of the mosaics are &sim;29 mag on a 0&farcs;35 diameter aperture. All the images have a pixel scale of 0&farcs;03.</p>\n</sec>\n<sec id=\"apjaaa6cfs2-2\">\n<label>2.2.</label>\n<title>Sample Selection</title>\n<p>We make two catalogs with different detection images, which are referred to as the<italic> JJHH</italic> and <italic>JHH</italic> catalogs. The detection image for the former is a <italic>J</italic><sub>125</sub>, <italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub>, and <italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub> combined image, and for the latter it is a <italic>JH</italic><sub>140</sub> and <italic>H</italic><sub>160</sub> combined image; these are created using <monospace>SWarp</monospace> v2.38.0 (Bertin et al. <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib9\">2002</xref>) together with their weight maps. To make the catalogs, we run <monospace>SExtractor</monospace> v2.8.6 (Bertin &amp; Arnouts <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib8\">1996</xref>) on the seven bands&rsquo; images using the detection images. The photometric redshifts of galaxies in these catalogs are estimated using <monospace>BPZ</monospace> v1.99.3 (Ben&iacute;tez <xref ref-type=\"bibr\" rid=\"apjaaa6cfbib7\">2000</xref>). From the catalogs, we select <italic>i</italic>-, <italic>Y</italic>-, and <italic>YJ</italic>-dropout galaxies using the Lyman break technique. For <italic>i</italic>- and <italic>Y</italic>-dropout selections, we use the <italic>JJHH</italic> catalog, and for <italic>YJ</italic>-dropout selection, we use the <italic>JHH</italic> catalog. For <italic>i</italic> dropouts or <italic>z</italic>&nbsp;&sim;&nbsp;6&ndash;7 galaxies, we use the criteria of<disp-formula id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn1\">\n<label>1</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA id=\"apjaaa6cfeqn9\">\n<label>9</label>\n<tex-math>\n<?CDATA \\begin{eqnarray}{J}_{125}-{H}_{160}\\lt 1.15,\\end{eqnarray}?>\n</tex-math>\n<!-- <mml:math>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>J</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>125</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo>\n<mml:msub>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mi>H</mml:mi>\n</mml:mrow>\n<mml:mrow>\n<mml:mn>160</mml:mn>\n</mml:mrow>\n</mml:msub>\n<mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo>\n<mml:mn>1.15</mml:mn>\n<mml:mo>,</mml:mo>\n</mml:math>
